{"DRAMATIS PERSONAE":{"1":{"play":"KING RICHARD THE SECOND","notes":[]},"2":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT, Duke of Lancaster, Uncle to the King","notes":[]},"3":{"play":"EDMUND OF LANGLEY, Duke of York, Uncles to the King","notes":[]},"4":{"play":"HENRY, surnamed Bolingbroke, Duke of Hereford, Son to John of Gaunt; afterwards King Henry IV","notes":[]},"5":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE, Son to the Duke of York","notes":[]},"6":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY, Duke of Norfolk","notes":[]},"7":{"play":"DUKE OF SURREY","notes":[]},"8":{"play":"EARL OF SALISBURY","notes":[]},"9":{"play":"LORD BERKELEY","notes":[]},"10":{"play":"BUSHY, Servants to King Richard","notes":[]},"11":{"play":"BAGOT, Servants to King Richard","notes":[]},"12":{"play":"GREEN, Servants to King Richard","notes":[]},"13":{"play":"EARL OF NORTHUMBERLAND","notes":[]},"14":{"play":"HENRY PERCY, surnamed Hotspur, his son","notes":[]},"15":{"play":"LORD ROSS","notes":[]},"16":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY","notes":[]},"17":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER","notes":[]},"18":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE","notes":[]},"19":{"play":"ABBOT OF WESTMINSTER","notes":[]},"20":{"play":"LORD MARSHAL","notes":[]},"21":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP","notes":[]},"22":{"play":"SIR PIERCE OF EXTON","notes":[]},"23":{"play":"CAPTAIN OF A BAND OF WELSHMEN","notes":[]},"24":{"play":"QUEEN TO KING RICHARD","notes":[]},"25":{"play":"DUCHESS OF GLOUCESTER","notes":[]},"26":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK","notes":[]},"27":{"play":"LADY ATTENDING ON THE QUEEN","notes":[]},"28":{"play":"Lords, Heralds, Officers, Soldiers, two Gardeners, Keeper, Messenger, Groom, and other Attendants","notes":[]}},"ACT 1 SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter KING RICHARD II, JOHN OF GAUNT, with other Nobles and Attendants]"},"2":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Old John of Gaunt, time-honour'd Lancaster,"},"3":{"play":"Hast thou, according to thy oath and band,"},"4":{"play":"Brought hither Henry Hereford thy bold son,"},"5":{"play":"Here to make good the boisterous late appeal,"},"6":{"play":"Which then our leisure would not let us hear,"},"7":{"play":"Against the Duke of Norfolk, Thomas Mowbray?"},"8":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: I have, my liege."},"9":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Tell me, moreover, hast thou sounded him,"},"10":{"play":"If he appeal the duke on ancient malice;"},"11":{"play":"Or worthily, as a good subject should,"},"12":{"play":"On some known ground of treachery in him?"},"13":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: As near as I could sift him on that argument,"},"14":{"play":"On some apparent danger seen in him"},"15":{"play":"Aim'd at your highness, no inveterate malice."},"16":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Then call them to our presence; face to face,"},"17":{"play":"And frowning brow to brow, ourselves will hear"},"18":{"play":"The accuser and the accused freely speak:"},"19":{"play":"High-stomach'd are they both, and full of ire,"},"20":{"play":"In rage deaf as the sea, hasty as fire."},"21":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Many years of happy days befal"},"22":{"play":"My gracious sovereign, my most loving liege!"},"23":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Each day still better other's happiness;"},"24":{"play":"Until the heavens, envying earth's good hap,"},"25":{"play":"Add an immortal title to your crown!"},"26":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We thank you both: yet one but flatters us,"},"27":{"play":"As well appeareth by the cause you come;"},"28":{"play":"Namely to appeal each other of high treason."},"29":{"play":"Cousin of Hereford, what dost thou object"},"30":{"play":"Against the Duke of Norfolk, Thomas Mowbray?"},"31":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: First, heaven be the record to my speech!"},"32":{"play":"In the devotion of a subject's love,"},"33":{"play":"Tendering the precious safety of my prince,"},"34":{"play":"And free from other misbegotten hate,"},"35":{"play":"Come I appellant to this princely presence."},"36":{"play":"Now, Thomas Mowbray, do I turn to thee,"},"37":{"play":"And mark my greeting well; for what I speak"},"38":{"play":"My body shall make good upon this earth,"},"39":{"play":"Or my divine soul answer it in heaven."},"40":{"play":"Thou art a traitor and a miscreant,"},"41":{"play":"Too good to be so and too bad to live,"},"42":{"play":"Since the more fair and crystal is the sky,"},"43":{"play":"The uglier seem the clouds that in it fly."},"44":{"play":"Once more, the more to aggravate the note,"},"45":{"play":"With a foul traitor's name stuff I thy throat;"},"46":{"play":"And wish, so please my sovereign, ere I move,"},"47":{"play":"What my tongue speaks my right drawn sword may prove."},"48":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Let not my cold words here accuse my zeal:"},"49":{"play":"'Tis not the trial of a woman's war,"},"50":{"play":"The bitter clamour of two eager tongues,"},"51":{"play":"Can arbitrate this cause betwixt us twain;"},"52":{"play":"The blood is hot that must be cool'd for this:"},"53":{"play":"Yet can I not of such tame patience boast"},"54":{"play":"As to be hush'd and nought at all to say:"},"55":{"play":"First, the fair reverence of your highness curbs me"},"56":{"play":"From giving reins and spurs to my free speech;"},"57":{"play":"Which else would post until it had return'd"},"58":{"play":"These terms of treason doubled down his throat."},"59":{"play":"Setting aside his high blood's royalty,"},"60":{"play":"And let him be no kinsman to my liege,"},"61":{"play":"I do defy him, and I spit at him;"},"62":{"play":"Call him a slanderous coward and a villain:"},"63":{"play":"Which to maintain I would allow him odds,"},"64":{"play":"And meet him, were I tied to run afoot"},"65":{"play":"Even to the frozen ridges of the Alps,"},"66":{"play":"Or any other ground inhabitable,"},"67":{"play":"Where ever Englishman durst set his foot."},"68":{"play":"Mean time let this defend my loyalty,"},"69":{"play":"By all my hopes, most falsely doth he lie."},"70":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Pale trembling coward, there I throw my gage,"},"71":{"play":"Disclaiming here the kindred of the king,"},"72":{"play":"And lay aside my high blood's royalty,"},"73":{"play":"Which fear, not reverence, makes thee to except."},"74":{"play":"If guilty dread have left thee so much strength"},"75":{"play":"As to take up mine honour's pawn, then stoop:"},"76":{"play":"By that and all the rites of knighthood else,"},"77":{"play":"Will I make good against thee, arm to arm,"},"78":{"play":"What I have spoke, or thou canst worse devise."},"79":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: I take it up; and by that sword I swear"},"80":{"play":"Which gently laid my knighthood on my shoulder,"},"81":{"play":"I'll answer thee in any fair degree,"},"82":{"play":"Or chivalrous design of knightly trial:"},"83":{"play":"And when I mount, alive may I not light,"},"84":{"play":"If I be traitor or unjustly fight!"},"85":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: What doth our cousin lay to Mowbray's charge?"},"86":{"play":"It must be great that can inherit us"},"87":{"play":"So much as of a thought of ill in him."},"88":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Look, what I speak, my life shall prove it true;"},"89":{"play":"That Mowbray hath received eight thousand nobles"},"90":{"play":"In name of lendings for your highness' soldiers,"},"91":{"play":"The which he hath detain'd for lewd employments,"},"92":{"play":"Like a false traitor and injurious villain."},"93":{"play":"Besides I say and will in battle prove,"},"94":{"play":"Or here or elsewhere to the furthest verge"},"95":{"play":"That ever was survey'd by English eye,"},"96":{"play":"That all the treasons for these eighteen years"},"97":{"play":"Complotted and contrived in this land"},"98":{"play":"Fetch from false Mowbray their first head and spring."},"99":{"play":"Further I say and further will maintain"},"100":{"play":"Upon his bad life to make all this good,"},"101":{"play":"That he did plot the Duke of Gloucester's death,"},"102":{"play":"Suggest his soon-believing adversaries,"},"103":{"play":"And consequently, like a traitor coward,"},"104":{"play":"Sluiced out his innocent soul through streams of blood:"},"105":{"play":"Which blood, like sacrificing Abel's, cries,"},"106":{"play":"Even from the tongueless caverns of the earth,"},"107":{"play":"To me for justice and rough chastisement;"},"108":{"play":"And, by the glorious worth of my descent,"},"109":{"play":"This arm shall do it, or this life be spent."},"110":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: How high a pitch his resolution soars!"},"111":{"play":"Thomas of Norfolk, what say'st thou to this?"},"112":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: O, let my sovereign turn away his face"},"113":{"play":"And bid his ears a little while be deaf,"},"114":{"play":"Till I have told this slander of his blood,"},"115":{"play":"How God and good men hate so foul a liar."},"116":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Mowbray, impartial are our eyes and ears:"},"117":{"play":"Were he my brother, nay, my kingdom's heir,"},"118":{"play":"As he is but my father's brother's son,"},"119":{"play":"Now, by my sceptre's awe, I make a vow,"},"120":{"play":"Such neighbour nearness to our sacred blood"},"121":{"play":"Should nothing privilege him, nor partialize"},"122":{"play":"The unstooping firmness of my upright soul:"},"123":{"play":"He is our subject, Mowbray; so art thou:"},"124":{"play":"Free speech and fearless I to thee allow."},"125":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Then, Bolingbroke, as low as to thy heart,"},"126":{"play":"Through the false passage of thy throat, thou liest."},"127":{"play":"Three parts of that receipt I had for Calais"},"128":{"play":"Disbursed I duly to his highness' soldiers;"},"129":{"play":"The other part reserved I by consent,"},"130":{"play":"For that my sovereign liege was in my debt"},"131":{"play":"Upon remainder of a dear account,"},"132":{"play":"Since last I went to France to fetch his queen:"},"133":{"play":"Now swallow down that lie. For Gloucester's death,"},"134":{"play":"I slew him not; but to my own disgrace"},"135":{"play":"Neglected my sworn duty in that case."},"136":{"play":"For you, my noble Lord of Lancaster,"},"137":{"play":"The honourable father to my foe"},"138":{"play":"Once did I lay an ambush for your life,"},"139":{"play":"A trespass that doth vex my grieved soul"},"140":{"play":"But ere I last received the sacrament"},"141":{"play":"I did confess it, and exactly begg'd"},"142":{"play":"Your grace's pardon, and I hope I had it."},"143":{"play":"This is my fault: as for the rest appeall'd,"},"144":{"play":"It issues from the rancour of a villain,"},"145":{"play":"A recreant and most degenerate traitor"},"146":{"play":"Which in myself I boldly will defend;"},"147":{"play":"And interchangeably hurl down my gage"},"148":{"play":"Upon this overweening traitor's foot,"},"149":{"play":"To prove myself a loyal gentleman"},"150":{"play":"Even in the best blood chamber'd in his bosom."},"151":{"play":"In haste whereof, most heartily I pray"},"152":{"play":"Your highness to assign our trial day."},"153":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Wrath-kindled gentlemen, be ruled by me;"},"154":{"play":"Let's purge this choler without letting blood:"},"155":{"play":"This we prescribe, though no physician;"},"156":{"play":"Deep malice makes too deep incision;"},"157":{"play":"Forget, forgive; conclude and be agreed;"},"158":{"play":"Our doctors say this is no month to bleed."},"159":{"play":"Good uncle, let this end where it begun;"},"160":{"play":"We'll calm the Duke of Norfolk, you your son."},"161":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: To be a make-peace shall become my age:"},"162":{"play":"Throw down, my son, the Duke of Norfolk's gage."},"163":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: And, Norfolk, throw down his."},"164":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: When, Harry, when?"},"165":{"play":"Obedience bids I should not bid again."},"166":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Norfolk, throw down, we bid; there is no boot."},"167":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Myself I throw, dread sovereign, at thy foot."},"168":{"play":"My life thou shalt command, but not my shame:"},"169":{"play":"The one my duty owes; but my fair name,"},"170":{"play":"Despite of death that lives upon my grave,"},"171":{"play":"To dark dishonour's use thou shalt not have."},"172":{"play":"I am disgraced, impeach'd and baffled here,"},"173":{"play":"Pierced to the soul with slander's venom'd spear,"},"174":{"play":"The which no balm can cure but his heart-blood"},"175":{"play":"Which breathed this poison."},"176":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Rage must be withstood:"},"177":{"play":"Give me his gage: lions make leopards tame."},"178":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Yea, but not change his spots: take but my shame."},"179":{"play":"And I resign my gage. My dear dear lord,"},"180":{"play":"The purest treasure mortal times afford"},"181":{"play":"Is spotless reputation: that away,"},"182":{"play":"Men are but gilded loam or painted clay."},"183":{"play":"A jewel in a ten-times-barr'd-up chest"},"184":{"play":"Is a bold spirit in a loyal breast."},"185":{"play":"Mine honour is my life; both grow in one:"},"186":{"play":"Take honour from me, and my life is done:"},"187":{"play":"Then, dear my liege, mine honour let me try;"},"188":{"play":"In that I live and for that will I die."},"189":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Cousin, throw up your gage; do you begin."},"190":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: O, God defend my soul from such deep sin!"},"191":{"play":"Shall I seem crest-fall'n in my father's sight?"},"192":{"play":"Or with pale beggar-fear impeach my height"},"193":{"play":"Before this out-dared dastard? Ere my tongue"},"194":{"play":"Shall wound my honour with such feeble wrong,"},"195":{"play":"Or sound so base a parle, my teeth shall tear"},"196":{"play":"The slavish motive of recanting fear,"},"197":{"play":"And spit it bleeding in his high disgrace,"},"198":{"play":"Where shame doth harbour, even in Mowbray's face."},"199":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We were not born to sue, but to command;"},"200":{"play":"Which since we cannot do to make you friends,"},"201":{"play":"Be ready, as your lives shall answer it,"},"202":{"play":"At Coventry, upon Saint Lambert's day:"},"203":{"play":"There shall your swords and lances arbitrate"},"204":{"play":"The swelling difference of your settled hate:"},"205":{"play":"Since we can not atone you, we shall see"},"206":{"play":"Justice design the victor's chivalry."},"207":{"play":"Lord marshal, command our officers at arms"},"208":{"play":"Be ready to direct these home alarms."}},"ACT 1 SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter JOHN OF GAUNT with DUCHESS]"},"2":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Alas, the part I had in Woodstock's blood"},"3":{"play":"Doth more solicit me than your exclaims,"},"4":{"play":"To stir against the butchers of his life!"},"5":{"play":"But since correction lieth in those hands"},"6":{"play":"Which made the fault that we cannot correct,"},"7":{"play":"Put we our quarrel to the will of heaven;"},"8":{"play":"Who, when they see the hours ripe on earth,"},"9":{"play":"Will rain hot vengeance on offenders' heads."},"10":{"play":"DUCHESS: Finds brotherhood in thee no sharper spur?"},"11":{"play":"Hath love in thy old blood no living fire?"},"12":{"play":"Edward's seven sons, whereof thyself art one,"},"13":{"play":"Were as seven vials of his sacred blood,"},"14":{"play":"Or seven fair branches springing from one root:"},"15":{"play":"Some of those seven are dried by nature's course,"},"16":{"play":"Some of those branches by the Destinies cut;"},"17":{"play":"But Thomas, my dear lord, my life, my Gloucester,"},"18":{"play":"One vial full of Edward's sacred blood,"},"19":{"play":"One flourishing branch of his most royal root,"},"20":{"play":"Is crack'd, and all the precious liquor spilt,"},"21":{"play":"Is hack'd down, and his summer leaves all faded,"},"22":{"play":"By envy's hand and murder's bloody axe."},"23":{"play":"Ah, Gaunt, his blood was thine! that bed, that womb,"},"24":{"play":"That metal, that self-mould, that fashion'd thee"},"25":{"play":"Made him a man; and though thou livest and breathest,"},"26":{"play":"Yet art thou slain in him: thou dost consent"},"27":{"play":"In some large measure to thy father's death,"},"28":{"play":"In that thou seest thy wretched brother die,"},"29":{"play":"Who was the model of thy father's life."},"30":{"play":"Call it not patience, Gaunt; it is despair:"},"31":{"play":"In suffering thus thy brother to be slaughter'd,"},"32":{"play":"Thou showest the naked pathway to thy life,"},"33":{"play":"Teaching stern murder how to butcher thee:"},"34":{"play":"That which in mean men we intitle patience"},"35":{"play":"Is pale cold cowardice in noble breasts."},"36":{"play":"What shall I say? to safeguard thine own life,"},"37":{"play":"The best way is to venge my Gloucester's death."},"38":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: God's is the quarrel; for God's substitute,"},"39":{"play":"His deputy anointed in His sight,"},"40":{"play":"Hath caused his death: the which if wrongfully,"},"41":{"play":"Let heaven revenge; for I may never lift"},"42":{"play":"An angry arm against His minister."},"43":{"play":"DUCHESS: Where then, alas, may I complain myself?"},"44":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: To God, the widow's champion and defence."},"45":{"play":"DUCHESS: Why, then, I will. Farewell, old Gaunt."},"46":{"play":"Thou goest to Coventry, there to behold"},"47":{"play":"Our cousin Hereford and fell Mowbray fight:"},"48":{"play":"O, sit my husband's wrongs on Hereford's spear,"},"49":{"play":"That it may enter butcher Mowbray's breast!"},"50":{"play":"Or, if misfortune miss the first career,"},"51":{"play":"Be Mowbray's sins so heavy in his bosom,"},"52":{"play":"They may break his foaming courser's back,"},"53":{"play":"And throw the rider headlong in the lists,"},"54":{"play":"A caitiff recreant to my cousin Hereford!"},"55":{"play":"Farewell, old Gaunt: thy sometimes brother's wife"},"56":{"play":"With her companion grief must end her life."},"57":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Sister, farewell; I must to Coventry:"},"58":{"play":"As much good stay with thee as go with me!"},"59":{"play":"DUCHESS: Yet one word more: grief boundeth where it falls,"},"60":{"play":"Not with the empty hollowness, but weight:"},"61":{"play":"I take my leave before I have begun,"},"62":{"play":"For sorrow ends not when it seemeth done."},"63":{"play":"Commend me to thy brother, Edmund York."},"64":{"play":"Lo, this is all:--nay, yet depart not so;"},"65":{"play":"Though this be all, do not so quickly go;"},"66":{"play":"I shall remember more. Bid him--ah, what?--"},"67":{"play":"With all good speed at Plashy visit me."},"68":{"play":"Alack, and what shall good old York there see"},"69":{"play":"But empty lodgings and unfurnish'd walls,"},"70":{"play":"Unpeopled offices, untrodden stones?"},"71":{"play":"And what hear there for welcome but my groans?"},"72":{"play":"Therefore commend me; let him not come there,"},"73":{"play":"To seek out sorrow that dwells every where."},"74":{"play":"Desolate, desolate, will I hence and die:"},"75":{"play":"The last leave of thee takes my weeping eye."}},"ACT 1 SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter the Lord Marshal and the DUKE OF AUMERLE]"},"2":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Yea, at all points; and longs to enter in."},"3":{"play":"Why, then, the champions are prepared, and stay"},"4":{"play":"For nothing but his majesty's approach."},"5":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Marshal, demand of yonder champion"},"6":{"play":"The cause of his arrival here in arms:"},"7":{"play":"Ask him his name and orderly proceed"},"8":{"play":"To swear him in the justice of his cause."},"9":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: My name is Thomas Mowbray, Duke of Norfolk;"},"10":{"play":"Who hither come engaged by my oath--"},"11":{"play":"Which God defend a knight should violate!--"},"12":{"play":"Both to defend my loyalty and truth"},"13":{"play":"To God, my king and my succeeding issue,"},"14":{"play":"Against the Duke of Hereford that appeals me"},"15":{"play":"And, by the grace of God and this mine arm,"},"16":{"play":"To prove him, in defending of myself,"},"17":{"play":"A traitor to my God, my king, and me:"},"18":{"play":"And as I truly fight, defend me heaven!"},"19":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Marshal, ask yonder knight in arms,"},"20":{"play":"Both who he is and why he cometh hither"},"21":{"play":"Thus plated in habiliments of war,"},"22":{"play":"And formally, according to our law,"},"23":{"play":"Depose him in the justice of his cause."},"24":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Harry of Hereford, Lancaster and Derby"},"25":{"play":"Am I; who ready here do stand in arms,"},"26":{"play":"To prove, by God's grace and my body's valour,"},"27":{"play":"In lists, on Thomas Mowbray, Duke of Norfolk,"},"28":{"play":"That he is a traitor, foul and dangerous,"},"29":{"play":"To God of heaven, King Richard and to me;"},"30":{"play":"And as I truly fight, defend me heaven!"},"31":{"play":"Lord marshal, let me kiss my sovereign's hand,"},"32":{"play":"And bow my knee before his majesty:"},"33":{"play":"For Mowbray and myself are like two men"},"34":{"play":"That vow a long and weary pilgrimage;"},"35":{"play":"Then let us take a ceremonious leave"},"36":{"play":"And loving farewell of our several friends."},"37":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We will descend and fold him in our arms."},"38":{"play":"Cousin of Hereford, as thy cause is right,"},"39":{"play":"So be thy fortune in this royal fight!"},"40":{"play":"Farewell, my blood; which if to-day thou shed,"},"41":{"play":"Lament we may, but not revenge thee dead."},"42":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: O let no noble eye profane a tear"},"43":{"play":"For me, if I be gored with Mowbray's spear:"},"44":{"play":"As confident as is the falcon's flight"},"45":{"play":"Against a bird, do I with Mowbray fight."},"46":{"play":"My loving lord, I take my leave of you;"},"47":{"play":"Of you, my noble cousin, Lord Aumerle;"},"48":{"play":"Not sick, although I have to do with death,"},"49":{"play":"But lusty, young, and cheerly drawing breath."},"50":{"play":"Lo, as at English feasts, so I regreet"},"51":{"play":"The daintiest last, to make the end most sweet:"},"52":{"play":"O thou, the earthly author of my blood,"},"53":{"play":"Whose youthful spirit, in me regenerate,"},"54":{"play":"Doth with a twofold vigour lift me up"},"55":{"play":"To reach at victory above my head,"},"56":{"play":"Add proof unto mine armour with thy prayers;"},"57":{"play":"And with thy blessings steel my lance's point,"},"58":{"play":"That it may enter Mowbray's waxen coat,"},"59":{"play":"And furbish new the name of John a Gaunt,"},"60":{"play":"Even in the lusty havior of his son."},"61":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: God in thy good cause make thee prosperous!"},"62":{"play":"Be swift like lightning in the execution;"},"63":{"play":"And let thy blows, doubly redoubled,"},"64":{"play":"Fall like amazing thunder on the casque"},"65":{"play":"Of thy adverse pernicious enemy:"},"66":{"play":"Rouse up thy youthful blood, be valiant and live."},"67":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Mine innocency and Saint George to thrive!"},"68":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: However God or fortune cast my lot,"},"69":{"play":"There lives or dies, true to King Richard's throne,"},"70":{"play":"A loyal, just and upright gentleman:"},"71":{"play":"Never did captive with a freer heart"},"72":{"play":"Cast off his chains of bondage and embrace"},"73":{"play":"His golden uncontroll'd enfranchisement,"},"74":{"play":"More than my dancing soul doth celebrate"},"75":{"play":"This feast of battle with mine adversary."},"76":{"play":"Most mighty liege, and my companion peers,"},"77":{"play":"Take from my mouth the wish of happy years:"},"78":{"play":"As gentle and as jocund as to jest"},"79":{"play":"Go I to fight: truth hath a quiet breast."},"80":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Farewell, my lord: securely I espy"},"81":{"play":"Virtue with valour couched in thine eye."},"82":{"play":"Order the trial, marshal, and begin."},"83":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Strong as a tower in hope, I cry amen."},"84":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Let them lay by their helmets and their spears,"},"85":{"play":"And both return back to their chairs again:"},"86":{"play":"Withdraw with us: and let the trumpets sound"},"87":{"play":"While we return these dukes what we decree."},"88":{"play":"Draw near,"},"89":{"play":"And list what with our council we have done."},"90":{"play":"For that our kingdom's earth should not be soil'd"},"91":{"play":"With that dear blood which it hath fostered;"},"92":{"play":"And for our eyes do hate the dire aspect"},"93":{"play":"Of civil wounds plough'd up with neighbours' sword;"},"94":{"play":"And for we think the eagle-winged pride"},"95":{"play":"Of sky-aspiring and ambitious thoughts,"},"96":{"play":"With rival-hating envy, set on you"},"97":{"play":"To wake our peace, which in our country's cradle"},"98":{"play":"Draws the sweet infant breath of gentle sleep;"},"99":{"play":"Which so roused up with boisterous untuned drums,"},"100":{"play":"With harsh resounding trumpets' dreadful bray,"},"101":{"play":"And grating shock of wrathful iron arms,"},"102":{"play":"Might from our quiet confines fright fair peace"},"103":{"play":"And make us wade even in our kindred's blood,"},"104":{"play":"Therefore, we banish you our territories:"},"105":{"play":"You, cousin Hereford, upon pain of life,"},"106":{"play":"Till twice five summers have enrich'd our fields"},"107":{"play":"Shall not regreet our fair dominions,"},"108":{"play":"But tread the stranger paths of banishment."},"109":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Your will be done: this must my comfort be,"},"110":{"play":"Sun that warms you here shall shine on me;"},"111":{"play":"And those his golden beams to you here lent"},"112":{"play":"Shall point on me and gild my banishment."},"113":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Norfolk, for thee remains a heavier doom,"},"114":{"play":"Which I with some unwillingness pronounce:"},"115":{"play":"The sly slow hours shall not determinate"},"116":{"play":"The dateless limit of thy dear exile;"},"117":{"play":"The hopeless word of 'never to return'"},"118":{"play":"Breathe I against thee, upon pain of life."},"119":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: A heavy sentence, my most sovereign liege,"},"120":{"play":"And all unlook'd for from your highness' mouth:"},"121":{"play":"A dearer merit, not so deep a maim"},"122":{"play":"As to be cast forth in the common air,"},"123":{"play":"Have I deserved at your highness' hands."},"124":{"play":"The language I have learn'd these forty years,"},"125":{"play":"My native English, now I must forego:"},"126":{"play":"And now my tongue's use is to me no more"},"127":{"play":"Than an unstringed viol or a harp,"},"128":{"play":"Or like a cunning instrument cased up,"},"129":{"play":"Or, being open, put into his hands"},"130":{"play":"That knows no touch to tune the harmony:"},"131":{"play":"Within my mouth you have engaol'd my tongue,"},"132":{"play":"Doubly portcullis'd with my teeth and lips;"},"133":{"play":"And dull unfeeling barren ignorance"},"134":{"play":"Is made my gaoler to attend on me."},"135":{"play":"I am too old to fawn upon a nurse,"},"136":{"play":"Too far in years to be a pupil now:"},"137":{"play":"What is thy sentence then but speechless death,"},"138":{"play":"Which robs my tongue from breathing native breath?"},"139":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: It boots thee not to be compassionate:"},"140":{"play":"After our sentence plaining comes too late."},"141":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: Then thus I turn me from my country's light,"},"142":{"play":"To dwell in solemn shades of endless night."},"143":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Return again, and take an oath with thee."},"144":{"play":"Lay on our royal sword your banish'd hands;"},"145":{"play":"Swear by the duty that you owe to God--"},"146":{"play":"Our part therein we banish with yourselves--"},"147":{"play":"To keep the oath that we administer:"},"148":{"play":"You never shall, so help you truth and God!"},"149":{"play":"Embrace each other's love in banishment;"},"150":{"play":"Nor never look upon each other's face;"},"151":{"play":"Nor never write, regreet, nor reconcile"},"152":{"play":"This louring tempest of your home-bred hate;"},"153":{"play":"Nor never by advised purpose meet"},"154":{"play":"To plot, contrive, or complot any ill"},"155":{"play":"'Gainst us, our state, our subjects, or our land."},"156":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I swear."},"157":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: And I, to keep all this."},"158":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Norfolk, so far as to mine enemy:--"},"159":{"play":"By this time, had the king permitted us,"},"160":{"play":"One of our souls had wander'd in the air."},"161":{"play":"Banish'd this frail sepulchre of our flesh,"},"162":{"play":"As now our flesh is banish'd from this land:"},"163":{"play":"Confess thy treasons ere thou fly the realm;"},"164":{"play":"Since thou hast far to go, bear not along"},"165":{"play":"The clogging burthen of a guilty soul."},"166":{"play":"THOMAS MOWBRAY: No, Bolingbroke: if ever I were traitor,"},"167":{"play":"My name be blotted from the book of life,"},"168":{"play":"And I from heaven banish'd as from hence!"},"169":{"play":"But what thou art, God, thou, and I do know;"},"170":{"play":"And all too soon, I fear, the king shall rue."},"171":{"play":"Farewell, my liege. Now no way can I stray;"},"172":{"play":"Save back to England, all the world's my way."},"173":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Uncle, even in the glasses of thine eyes"},"174":{"play":"I see thy grieved heart: thy sad aspect"},"175":{"play":"Hath from the number of his banish'd years"},"176":{"play":"Pluck'd four away."},"177":{"play":"Six frozen winter spent,"},"178":{"play":"Return with welcome home from banishment."},"179":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: How long a time lies in one little word!"},"180":{"play":"Four lagging winters and four wanton springs"},"181":{"play":"End in a word: such is the breath of kings."},"182":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: I thank my liege, that in regard of me"},"183":{"play":"He shortens four years of my son's exile:"},"184":{"play":"But little vantage shall I reap thereby;"},"185":{"play":"For, ere the six years that he hath to spend"},"186":{"play":"Can change their moons and bring their times about"},"187":{"play":"My oil-dried lamp and time-bewasted light"},"188":{"play":"Shall be extinct with age and endless night;"},"189":{"play":"My inch of taper will be burnt and done,"},"190":{"play":"And blindfold death not let me see my son."},"191":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Why uncle, thou hast many years to live."},"192":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: But not a minute, king, that thou canst give:"},"193":{"play":"Shorten my days thou canst with sullen sorrow,"},"194":{"play":"And pluck nights from me, but not lend a morrow;"},"195":{"play":"Thou canst help time to furrow me with age,"},"196":{"play":"But stop no wrinkle in his pilgrimage;"},"197":{"play":"Thy word is current with him for my death,"},"198":{"play":"But dead, thy kingdom cannot buy my breath."},"199":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Thy son is banish'd upon good advice,"},"200":{"play":"Whereto thy tongue a party-verdict gave:"},"201":{"play":"Why at our justice seem'st thou then to lour?"},"202":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Things sweet to taste prove in digestion sour."},"203":{"play":"You urged me as a judge; but I had rather"},"204":{"play":"You would have bid me argue like a father."},"205":{"play":"O, had it been a stranger, not my child,"},"206":{"play":"To smooth his fault I should have been more mild:"},"207":{"play":"A partial slander sought I to avoid,"},"208":{"play":"And in the sentence my own life destroy'd."},"209":{"play":"Alas, I look'd when some of you should say,"},"210":{"play":"I was too strict to make mine own away;"},"211":{"play":"But you gave leave to my unwilling tongue"},"212":{"play":"Against my will to do myself this wrong."},"213":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Cousin, farewell; and, uncle, bid him so:"},"214":{"play":"Six years we banish him, and he shall go."},"215":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Cousin, farewell: what presence must not know,"},"216":{"play":"From where you do remain let paper show."},"217":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: O, to what purpose dost thou hoard thy words,"},"218":{"play":"That thou return'st no greeting to thy friends?"},"219":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I have too few to take my leave of you,"},"220":{"play":"When the tongue's office should be prodigal"},"221":{"play":"To breathe the abundant dolour of the heart."},"222":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Thy grief is but thy absence for a time."},"223":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Joy absent, grief is present for that time."},"224":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: What is six winters? they are quickly gone."},"225":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: To men in joy; but grief makes one hour ten."},"226":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Call it a travel that thou takest for pleasure."},"227":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My heart will sigh when I miscall it so,"},"228":{"play":"Which finds it an inforced pilgrimage."},"229":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: The sullen passage of thy weary steps"},"230":{"play":"Esteem as foil wherein thou art to set"},"231":{"play":"The precious jewel of thy home return."},"232":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Nay, rather, every tedious stride I make"},"233":{"play":"Will but remember me what a deal of world"},"234":{"play":"I wander from the jewels that I love."},"235":{"play":"Must I not serve a long apprenticehood"},"236":{"play":"To foreign passages, and in the end,"},"237":{"play":"Having my freedom, boast of nothing else"},"238":{"play":"But that I was a journeyman to grief?"},"239":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: All places that the eye of heaven visits"},"240":{"play":"Are to a wise man ports and happy havens."},"241":{"play":"Teach thy necessity to reason thus;"},"242":{"play":"There is no virtue like necessity."},"243":{"play":"Think not the king did banish thee,"},"244":{"play":"But thou the king. Woe doth the heavier sit,"},"245":{"play":"Where it perceives it is but faintly borne."},"246":{"play":"Go, say I sent thee forth to purchase honour"},"247":{"play":"And not the king exiled thee; or suppose"},"248":{"play":"Devouring pestilence hangs in our air"},"249":{"play":"And thou art flying to a fresher clime:"},"250":{"play":"Look, what thy soul holds dear, imagine it"},"251":{"play":"To lie that way thou go'st, not whence thou comest:"},"252":{"play":"Suppose the singing birds musicians,"},"253":{"play":"The grass whereon thou tread'st the presence strew'd,"},"254":{"play":"The flowers fair ladies, and thy steps no more"},"255":{"play":"Than a delightful measure or a dance;"},"256":{"play":"For gnarling sorrow hath less power to bite"},"257":{"play":"The man that mocks at it and sets it light."},"258":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: O, who can hold a fire in his hand"},"259":{"play":"By thinking on the frosty Caucasus?"},"260":{"play":"Or cloy the hungry edge of appetite"},"261":{"play":"By bare imagination of a feast?"},"262":{"play":"Or wallow naked in December snow"},"263":{"play":"By thinking on fantastic summer's heat?"},"264":{"play":"O, no! the apprehension of the good"},"265":{"play":"Gives but the greater feeling to the worse:"},"266":{"play":"Fell sorrow's tooth doth never rankle more"},"267":{"play":"Than when he bites, but lanceth not the sore."},"268":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Come, come, my son, I'll bring thee on thy way:"},"269":{"play":"Had I thy youth and cause, I would not stay."},"270":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Then, England's ground, farewell; sweet soil, adieu;"},"271":{"play":"My mother, and my nurse, that bears me yet!"},"272":{"play":"Where'er I wander, boast of this I can,"},"273":{"play":"Though banish'd, yet a trueborn Englishman."}},"ACT 1 SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Enter KING RICHARD II, with BAGOT and GREEN at one door; and the DUKE OF AUMERLE at another]"},"2":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We did observe. Cousin Aumerle,"},"3":{"play":"How far brought you high Hereford on his way?"},"4":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: I brought high Hereford, if you call him so,"},"5":{"play":"But to the next highway, and there I left him."},"6":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: And say, what store of parting tears were shed?"},"7":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Faith, none for me; except the north-east wind,"},"8":{"play":"Which then blew bitterly against our faces,"},"9":{"play":"Awaked the sleeping rheum, and so by chance"},"10":{"play":"Did grace our hollow parting with a tear."},"11":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: What said our cousin when you parted with him?"},"12":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: 'Farewell:'"},"13":{"play":"And, for my heart disdained that my tongue"},"14":{"play":"Should so profane the word, that taught me craft"},"15":{"play":"To counterfeit oppression of such grief"},"16":{"play":"That words seem'd buried in my sorrow's grave."},"17":{"play":"Marry, would the word 'farewell' have lengthen'd hours"},"18":{"play":"And added years to his short banishment,"},"19":{"play":"He should have had a volume of farewells;"},"20":{"play":"But since it would not, he had none of me."},"21":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: He is our cousin, cousin; but 'tis doubt,"},"22":{"play":"When time shall call him home from banishment,"},"23":{"play":"Whether our kinsman come to see his friends."},"24":{"play":"Ourself and Bushy, Bagot here and Green"},"25":{"play":"Observed his courtship to the common people;"},"26":{"play":"How he did seem to dive into their hearts"},"27":{"play":"With humble and familiar courtesy,"},"28":{"play":"What reverence he did throw away on slaves,"},"29":{"play":"Wooing poor craftsmen with the craft of smiles"},"30":{"play":"And patient underbearing of his fortune,"},"31":{"play":"As 'twere to banish their affects with him."},"32":{"play":"Off goes his bonnet to an oyster-wench;"},"33":{"play":"A brace of draymen bid God speed him well"},"34":{"play":"And had the tribute of his supple knee,"},"35":{"play":"With 'Thanks, my countrymen, my loving friends;'"},"36":{"play":"As were our England in reversion his,"},"37":{"play":"And he our subjects' next degree in hope."},"38":{"play":"GREEN: Well, he is gone; and with him go these thoughts."},"39":{"play":"Now for the rebels which stand out in Ireland,"},"40":{"play":"Expedient manage must be made, my liege,"},"41":{"play":"Ere further leisure yield them further means"},"42":{"play":"For their advantage and your highness' loss."},"43":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We will ourself in person to this war:"},"44":{"play":"And, for our coffers, with too great a court"},"45":{"play":"And liberal largess, are grown somewhat light,"},"46":{"play":"We are inforced to farm our royal realm;"},"47":{"play":"The revenue whereof shall furnish us"},"48":{"play":"For our affairs in hand: if that come short,"},"49":{"play":"Our substitutes at home shall have blank charters;"},"50":{"play":"Whereto, when they shall know what men are rich,"},"51":{"play":"They shall subscribe them for large sums of gold"},"52":{"play":"And send them after to supply our wants;"},"53":{"play":"For we will make for Ireland presently."},"54":{"play":"Bushy, what news?"},"55":{"play":"BUSHY: Old John of Gaunt is grievous sick, my lord,"},"56":{"play":"Suddenly taken; and hath sent post haste"},"57":{"play":"To entreat your majesty to visit him."},"58":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Where lies he?"},"59":{"play":"BUSHY: At Ely House."},"60":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Now put it, God, in the physician's mind"},"61":{"play":"To help him to his grave immediately!"},"62":{"play":"The lining of his coffers shall make coats"},"63":{"play":"To deck our soldiers for these Irish wars."},"64":{"play":"Come, gentlemen, let's all go visit him:"},"65":{"play":"Pray God we may make haste, and come too late!"},"66":{"play":"[Exeunt]"}},"ACT 2 SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter JOHN OF GAUNT sick, with the DUKE OF YORK, & c]"},"2":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Will the king come, that I may breathe my last"},"3":{"play":"In wholesome counsel to his unstaid youth?"},"4":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Vex not yourself, nor strive not with your breath;"},"5":{"play":"For all in vain comes counsel to his ear."},"6":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: O, but they say the tongues of dying men"},"7":{"play":"Enforce attention like deep harmony:"},"8":{"play":"Where words are scarce, they are seldom spent in vain,"},"9":{"play":"For they breathe truth that breathe their words in pain."},"10":{"play":"He that no more must say is listen'd more"},"11":{"play":"Than they whom youth and ease have taught to glose;"},"12":{"play":"More are men's ends mark'd than their lives before:"},"13":{"play":"The setting sun, and music at the close,"},"14":{"play":"As the last taste of sweets, is sweetest last,"},"15":{"play":"Writ in remembrance more than things long past:"},"16":{"play":"Though Richard my life's counsel would not hear,"},"17":{"play":"My death's sad tale may yet undeaf his ear."},"18":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: No; it is stopp'd with other flattering sounds,"},"19":{"play":"As praises, of whose taste the wise are fond,"},"20":{"play":"Lascivious metres, to whose venom sound"},"21":{"play":"The open ear of youth doth always listen;"},"22":{"play":"Report of fashions in proud Italy,"},"23":{"play":"Whose manners still our tardy apish nation"},"24":{"play":"Limps after in base imitation."},"25":{"play":"Where doth the world thrust forth a vanity--"},"26":{"play":"So it be new, there's no respect how vile--"},"27":{"play":"That is not quickly buzzed into his ears?"},"28":{"play":"Then all too late comes counsel to be heard,"},"29":{"play":"Where will doth mutiny with wit's regard."},"30":{"play":"Direct not him whose way himself will choose:"},"31":{"play":"'Tis breath thou lack'st, and that breath wilt thou lose."},"32":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Methinks I am a prophet new inspired"},"33":{"play":"And thus expiring do foretell of him:"},"34":{"play":"His rash fierce blaze of riot cannot last,"},"35":{"play":"For violent fires soon burn out themselves;"},"36":{"play":"Small showers last long, but sudden storms are short;"},"37":{"play":"He tires betimes that spurs too fast betimes;"},"38":{"play":"With eager feeding food doth choke the feeder:"},"39":{"play":"Light vanity, insatiate cormorant,"},"40":{"play":"Consuming means, soon preys upon itself."},"41":{"play":"This royal throne of kings, this scepter'd isle,"},"42":{"play":"This earth of majesty, this seat of Mars,"},"43":{"play":"This other Eden, demi-paradise,"},"44":{"play":"This fortress built by Nature for herself"},"45":{"play":"Against infection and the hand of war,"},"46":{"play":"This happy breed of men, this little world,"},"47":{"play":"This precious stone set in the silver sea,"},"48":{"play":"Which serves it in the office of a wall,"},"49":{"play":"Or as a moat defensive to a house,"},"50":{"play":"Against the envy of less happier lands,"},"51":{"play":"This blessed plot, this earth, this realm, this England,"},"52":{"play":"This nurse, this teeming womb of royal kings,"},"53":{"play":"Fear'd by their breed and famous by their birth,"},"54":{"play":"Renowned for their deeds as far from home,"},"55":{"play":"For Christian service and true chivalry,"},"56":{"play":"As is the sepulchre in stubborn Jewry,"},"57":{"play":"Of the world's ransom, blessed Mary's Son,"},"58":{"play":"This land of such dear souls, this dear dear land,"},"59":{"play":"Dear for her reputation through the world,"},"60":{"play":"Is now leased out, I die pronouncing it,"},"61":{"play":"Like to a tenement or pelting farm:"},"62":{"play":"England, bound in with the triumphant sea"},"63":{"play":"Whose rocky shore beats back the envious siege"},"64":{"play":"Of watery Neptune, is now bound in with shame,"},"65":{"play":"With inky blots and rotten parchment bonds:"},"66":{"play":"That England, that was wont to conquer others,"},"67":{"play":"Hath made a shameful conquest of itself."},"68":{"play":"Ah, would the scandal vanish with my life,"},"69":{"play":"How happy then were my ensuing death!"},"70":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: The king is come: deal mildly with his youth;"},"71":{"play":"For young hot colts being raged do rage the more."},"72":{"play":"QUEEN: How fares our noble uncle, Lancaster?"},"73":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: What comfort, man? how is't with aged Gaunt?"},"74":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: O how that name befits my composition!"},"75":{"play":"Old Gaunt indeed, and gaunt in being old:"},"76":{"play":"Within me grief hath kept a tedious fast;"},"77":{"play":"And who abstains from meat that is not gaunt?"},"78":{"play":"For sleeping England long time have I watch'd;"},"79":{"play":"Watching breeds leanness, leanness is all gaunt:"},"80":{"play":"The pleasure that some fathers feed upon,"},"81":{"play":"Is my strict fast; I mean, my children's looks;"},"82":{"play":"And therein fasting, hast thou made me gaunt:"},"83":{"play":"Gaunt am I for the grave, gaunt as a grave,"},"84":{"play":"Whose hollow womb inherits nought but bones."},"85":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Can sick men play so nicely with their names?"},"86":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: No, misery makes sport to mock itself:"},"87":{"play":"Since thou dost seek to kill my name in me,"},"88":{"play":"I mock my name, great king, to flatter thee."},"89":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Should dying men flatter with those that live?"},"90":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: No, no, men living flatter those that die."},"91":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Thou, now a-dying, say'st thou flatterest me."},"92":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: O, no! thou diest, though I the sicker be."},"93":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: I am in health, I breathe, and see thee ill."},"94":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: Now He that made me knows I see thee ill;"},"95":{"play":"Ill in myself to see, and in thee seeing ill."},"96":{"play":"Thy death-bed is no lesser than thy land"},"97":{"play":"Wherein thou liest in reputation sick;"},"98":{"play":"And thou, too careless patient as thou art,"},"99":{"play":"Commit'st thy anointed body to the cure"},"100":{"play":"Of those physicians that first wounded thee:"},"101":{"play":"A thousand flatterers sit within thy crown,"},"102":{"play":"Whose compass is no bigger than thy head;"},"103":{"play":"And yet, incaged in so small a verge,"},"104":{"play":"The waste is no whit lesser than thy land."},"105":{"play":"O, had thy grandsire with a prophet's eye"},"106":{"play":"Seen how his son's son should destroy his sons,"},"107":{"play":"From forth thy reach he would have laid thy shame,"},"108":{"play":"Deposing thee before thou wert possess'd,"},"109":{"play":"Which art possess'd now to depose thyself."},"110":{"play":"Why, cousin, wert thou regent of the world,"},"111":{"play":"It were a shame to let this land by lease;"},"112":{"play":"But for thy world enjoying but this land,"},"113":{"play":"Is it not more than shame to shame it so?"},"114":{"play":"Landlord of England art thou now, not king:"},"115":{"play":"Thy state of law is bondslave to the law; And thou--"},"116":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: A lunatic lean-witted fool,"},"117":{"play":"Presuming on an ague's privilege,"},"118":{"play":"Darest with thy frozen admonition"},"119":{"play":"Make pale our cheek, chasing the royal blood"},"120":{"play":"With fury from his native residence."},"121":{"play":"Now, by my seat's right royal majesty,"},"122":{"play":"Wert thou not brother to great Edward's son,"},"123":{"play":"This tongue that runs so roundly in thy head"},"124":{"play":"Should run thy head from thy unreverent shoulders."},"125":{"play":"JOHN OF GAUNT: O, spare me not, my brother Edward's son,"},"126":{"play":"For that I was his father Edward's son;"},"127":{"play":"That blood already, like the pelican,"},"128":{"play":"Hast thou tapp'd out and drunkenly caroused:"},"129":{"play":"My brother Gloucester, plain well-meaning soul,"},"130":{"play":"Whom fair befal in heaven 'mongst happy souls!"},"131":{"play":"May be a precedent and witness good"},"132":{"play":"That thou respect'st not spilling Edward's blood:"},"133":{"play":"Join with the present sickness that I have;"},"134":{"play":"And thy unkindness be like crooked age,"},"135":{"play":"To crop at once a too long wither'd flower."},"136":{"play":"Live in thy shame, but die not shame with thee!"},"137":{"play":"These words hereafter thy tormentors be!"},"138":{"play":"Convey me to my bed, then to my grave:"},"139":{"play":"Love they to live that love and honour have."},"140":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: And let them die that age and sullens have;"},"141":{"play":"For both hast thou, and both become the grave."},"142":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: I do beseech your majesty, impute his words"},"143":{"play":"To wayward sickliness and age in him:"},"144":{"play":"He loves you, on my life, and holds you dear"},"145":{"play":"As Harry Duke of Hereford, were he here."},"146":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Right, you say true: as Hereford's love, so his;"},"147":{"play":"As theirs, so mine; and all be as it is."},"148":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My liege, old Gaunt commends him to your majesty."},"149":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: What says he?"},"150":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Nay, nothing; all is said"},"151":{"play":"His tongue is now a stringless instrument;"},"152":{"play":"Words, life and all, old Lancaster hath spent."},"153":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Be York the next that must be bankrupt so!"},"154":{"play":"Though death be poor, it ends a mortal woe."},"155":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: The ripest fruit first falls, and so doth he;"},"156":{"play":"His time is spent, our pilgrimage must be."},"157":{"play":"So much for that. Now for our Irish wars:"},"158":{"play":"We must supplant those rough rug-headed kerns,"},"159":{"play":"Which live like venom where no venom else"},"160":{"play":"But only they have privilege to live."},"161":{"play":"And for these great affairs do ask some charge,"},"162":{"play":"Towards our assistance we do seize to us"},"163":{"play":"The plate, corn, revenues and moveables,"},"164":{"play":"Whereof our uncle Gaunt did stand possess'd."},"165":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: How long shall I be patient? ah, how long"},"166":{"play":"Shall tender duty make me suffer wrong?"},"167":{"play":"Not Gloucester's death, nor Hereford's banishment"},"168":{"play":"Not Gaunt's rebukes, nor England's private wrongs,"},"169":{"play":"Nor the prevention of poor Bolingbroke"},"170":{"play":"About his marriage, nor my own disgrace,"},"171":{"play":"Have ever made me sour my patient cheek,"},"172":{"play":"Or bend one wrinkle on my sovereign's face."},"173":{"play":"I am the last of noble Edward's sons,"},"174":{"play":"Of whom thy father, Prince of Wales, was first:"},"175":{"play":"In war was never lion raged more fierce,"},"176":{"play":"In peace was never gentle lamb more mild,"},"177":{"play":"Than was that young and princely gentleman."},"178":{"play":"His face thou hast, for even so look'd he,"},"179":{"play":"Accomplish'd with the number of thy hours;"},"180":{"play":"But when he frown'd, it was against the French"},"181":{"play":"And not against his friends; his noble hand"},"182":{"play":"Did will what he did spend and spent not that"},"183":{"play":"Which his triumphant father's hand had won;"},"184":{"play":"His hands were guilty of no kindred blood,"},"185":{"play":"But bloody with the enemies of his kin."},"186":{"play":"O Richard! York is too far gone with grief,"},"187":{"play":"Or else he never would compare between."},"188":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Why, uncle, what's the matter?"},"189":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: O my liege,"},"190":{"play":"Pardon me, if you please; if n ot, I, pleased"},"191":{"play":"Not to be pardon'd, am content withal."},"192":{"play":"Seek you to seize and gripe into your hands"},"193":{"play":"The royalties and rights of banish'd Hereford?"},"194":{"play":"Is not Gaunt dead, and doth not Hereford live?"},"195":{"play":"Was not Gaunt just, and is not Harry true?"},"196":{"play":"Did not the one deserve to have an heir?"},"197":{"play":"Is not his heir a well-deserving son?"},"198":{"play":"Take Hereford's rights away, and take from Time"},"199":{"play":"His charters and his customary rights;"},"200":{"play":"Let not to-morrow then ensue to-day;"},"201":{"play":"Be not thyself; for how art thou a king"},"202":{"play":"But by fair sequence and succession?"},"203":{"play":"Now, afore God--God forbid I say true!--"},"204":{"play":"If you do wrongfully seize Hereford's rights,"},"205":{"play":"Call in the letters patent that he hath"},"206":{"play":"By his attorneys-general to sue"},"207":{"play":"His livery, and deny his offer'd homage,"},"208":{"play":"You pluck a thousand dangers on your head,"},"209":{"play":"You lose a thousand well-disposed hearts"},"210":{"play":"And prick my tender patience, to those thoughts"},"211":{"play":"Which honour and allegiance cannot think."},"212":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Think what you will, we seize into our hands"},"213":{"play":"His plate, his goods, his money and his lands."},"214":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: I'll not be by the while: my liege, farewell:"},"215":{"play":"What will ensue hereof, there's none can tell;"},"216":{"play":"But by bad courses may be understood"},"217":{"play":"That their events can never fall out good."},"218":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Go, Bushy, to the Earl of Wiltshire straight:"},"219":{"play":"Bid him repair to us to Ely House"},"220":{"play":"To see this business. To-morrow next"},"221":{"play":"We will for Ireland; and 'tis time, I trow:"},"222":{"play":"And we create, in absence of ourself,"},"223":{"play":"Our uncle York lord governor of England;"},"224":{"play":"For he is just and always loved us well."},"225":{"play":"Come on, our queen: to-morrow must we part;"},"226":{"play":"Be merry, for our time of stay is short"},"227":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Well, lords, the Duke of Lancaster is dead."},"228":{"play":"LORD ROSS: And living too; for now his son is duke."},"229":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: Barely in title, not in revenue."},"230":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Richly in both, if justice had her right."},"231":{"play":"LORD ROSS: My heart is great; but it must break with silence,"},"232":{"play":"Ere't be disburden'd with a liberal tongue."},"233":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Nay, speak thy mind; and let him ne'er speak more"},"234":{"play":"That speaks thy words again to do thee harm!"},"235":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: Tends that thou wouldst speak to the Duke of Hereford?"},"236":{"play":"If it be so, out with it boldly, man;"},"237":{"play":"Quick is mine ear to hear of good towards him."},"238":{"play":"LORD ROSS: No good at all that I can do for him;"},"239":{"play":"Unless you call it good to pity him,"},"240":{"play":"Bereft and gelded of his patrimony."},"241":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Now, afore God, 'tis shame such wrongs are borne"},"242":{"play":"In him, a royal prince, and many moe"},"243":{"play":"Of noble blood in this declining land."},"244":{"play":"The king is not himself, but basely led"},"245":{"play":"By flatterers; and what they will inform,"},"246":{"play":"Merely in hate, 'gainst any of us all,"},"247":{"play":"That will the king severely prosecute"},"248":{"play":"'Gainst us, our lives, our children, and our heirs."},"249":{"play":"LORD ROSS: The commons hath he pill'd with grievous taxes,"},"250":{"play":"And quite lost their hearts: the nobles hath he fined"},"251":{"play":"For ancient quarrels, and quite lost their hearts."},"252":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: And daily new exactions are devised,"},"253":{"play":"As blanks, benevolences, and I wot not what:"},"254":{"play":"But what, o' God's name, doth become of this?"},"255":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Wars have not wasted it, for warr'd he hath not,"},"256":{"play":"But basely yielded upon compromise"},"257":{"play":"That which his noble ancestors achieved with blows:"},"258":{"play":"More hath he spent in peace than they in wars."},"259":{"play":"LORD ROSS: The Earl of Wiltshire hath the realm in farm."},"260":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: The king's grown bankrupt, like a broken man."},"261":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Reproach and dissolution hangeth over him."},"262":{"play":"LORD ROSS: He hath not money for these Irish wars,"},"263":{"play":"His burthenous taxations notwithstanding,"},"264":{"play":"But by the robbing of the banish'd duke."},"265":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: His noble kinsman: most degenerate king!"},"266":{"play":"But, lords, we hear this fearful tempest sing,"},"267":{"play":"Yet see no shelter to avoid the storm;"},"268":{"play":"We see the wind sit sore upon our sails,"},"269":{"play":"And yet we strike not, but securely perish."},"270":{"play":"LORD ROSS: We see the very wreck that we must suffer;"},"271":{"play":"And unavoided is the danger now,"},"272":{"play":"For suffering so the causes of our wreck."},"273":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Not so; even through the hollow eyes of death"},"274":{"play":"I spy life peering; but I dare not say"},"275":{"play":"How near the tidings of our comfort is."},"276":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: Nay, let us share thy thoughts, as thou dost ours."},"277":{"play":"LORD ROSS: Be confident to speak, Northumberland:"},"278":{"play":"We three are but thyself; and, speaking so,"},"279":{"play":"Thy words are but as thoughts; therefore, be bold."},"280":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Then thus: I have from Port le Blanc, a bay"},"281":{"play":"In Brittany, received intelligence"},"282":{"play":"That Harry Duke of Hereford, Rainold Lord Cobham,"},"283":{"play":"That late broke from the Duke of Exeter,"},"284":{"play":"His brother, Archbishop late of Canterbury,"},"285":{"play":"Sir Thomas Erpingham, Sir John Ramston,"},"286":{"play":"Sir John Norbery, Sir Robert Waterton and Francis Quoint,"},"287":{"play":"All these well furnish'd by the Duke of Bretagne"},"288":{"play":"With eight tall ships, three thousand men of war,"},"289":{"play":"Are making hither with all due expedience"},"290":{"play":"And shortly mean to touch our northern shore:"},"291":{"play":"Perhaps they had ere this, but that they stay"},"292":{"play":"The first departing of the king for Ireland."},"293":{"play":"If then we shall shake off our slavish yoke,"},"294":{"play":"Imp out our drooping country's broken wing,"},"295":{"play":"Redeem from broking pawn the blemish'd crown,"},"296":{"play":"Wipe off the dust that hides our sceptre's gilt"},"297":{"play":"And make high majesty look like itself,"},"298":{"play":"Away with me in post to Ravenspurgh;"},"299":{"play":"But if you faint, as fearing to do so,"},"300":{"play":"Stay and be secret, and myself will go."},"301":{"play":"LORD ROSS: To horse, to horse! urge doubts to them that fear."},"302":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: Hold out my horse, and I will first be there."}},"ACT 2 SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter QUEEN, BUSHY, and BAGOT]"},"2":{"play":"BUSHY: Madam, your majesty is too much sad:"},"3":{"play":"You promised, when you parted with the king,"},"4":{"play":"To lay aside life-harming heaviness"},"5":{"play":"And entertain a cheerful disposition."},"6":{"play":"QUEEN: To please the king I did; to please myself"},"7":{"play":"I cannot do it; yet I know no cause"},"8":{"play":"Why I should welcome such a guest as grief,"},"9":{"play":"Save bidding farewell to so sweet a guest"},"10":{"play":"As my sweet Richard: yet again, methinks,"},"11":{"play":"Some unborn sorrow, ripe in fortune's womb,"},"12":{"play":"Is coming towards me, and my inward soul"},"13":{"play":"With nothing trembles: at some thing it grieves,"},"14":{"play":"More than with parting from my lord the king."},"15":{"play":"BUSHY: Each substance of a grief hath twenty shadows,"},"16":{"play":"Which shows like grief itself, but is not so;"},"17":{"play":"For sorrow's eye, glazed with blinding tears,"},"18":{"play":"Divides one thing entire to many objects;"},"19":{"play":"Like perspectives, which rightly gazed upon"},"20":{"play":"Show nothing but confusion, eyed awry"},"21":{"play":"Distinguish form: so your sweet majesty,"},"22":{"play":"Looking awry upon your lord's departure,"},"23":{"play":"Find shapes of grief, more than himself, to wail;"},"24":{"play":"Which, look'd on as it is, is nought but shadows"},"25":{"play":"Of what it is not. Then, thrice-gracious queen,"},"26":{"play":"More than your lord's departure weep not: more's not seen;"},"27":{"play":"Or if it be, 'tis with false sorrow's eye,"},"28":{"play":"Which for things true weeps things imaginary."},"29":{"play":"QUEEN: It may be so; but yet my inward soul"},"30":{"play":"Persuades me it is otherwise: howe'er it be,"},"31":{"play":"I cannot but be sad; so heavy sad"},"32":{"play":"As, though on thinking on no thought I think,"},"33":{"play":"Makes me with heavy nothing faint and shrink."},"34":{"play":"BUSHY: 'Tis nothing but conceit, my gracious lady."},"35":{"play":"QUEEN: 'Tis nothing less: conceit is still derived"},"36":{"play":"From some forefather grief; mine is not so,"},"37":{"play":"For nothing had begot my something grief;"},"38":{"play":"Or something hath the nothing that I grieve:"},"39":{"play":"'Tis in reversion that I do possess;"},"40":{"play":"But what it is, that is not yet known; what"},"41":{"play":"I cannot name; 'tis nameless woe, I wot."},"42":{"play":"GREEN: God save your majesty! and well met, gentlemen:"},"43":{"play":"I hope the king is not yet shipp'd for Ireland."},"44":{"play":"QUEEN: Why hopest thou so? 'tis better hope he is;"},"45":{"play":"For his designs crave haste, his haste good hope:"},"46":{"play":"Then wherefore dost thou hope he is not shipp'd?"},"47":{"play":"GREEN: That he, our hope, might have retired his power,"},"48":{"play":"And driven into despair an enemy's hope,"},"49":{"play":"Who strongly hath set footing in this land:"},"50":{"play":"The banish'd Bolingbroke repeals himself,"},"51":{"play":"And with uplifted arms is safe arrived"},"52":{"play":"At Ravenspurgh."},"53":{"play":"QUEEN: Now God in heaven forbid!"},"54":{"play":"GREEN: Ah, madam, 'tis too true: and that is worse,"},"55":{"play":"The Lord Northumberland, his son young Henry Percy,"},"56":{"play":"The Lords of Ross, Beaumond, and Willoughby,"},"57":{"play":"With all their powerful friends, are fled to him."},"58":{"play":"BUSHY: Why have you not proclaim'd Northumberland"},"59":{"play":"And all the rest revolted faction traitors?"},"60":{"play":"GREEN: We have: whereupon the Earl of Worcester"},"61":{"play":"Hath broke his staff, resign'd his stewardship,"},"62":{"play":"And all the household servants fled with him"},"63":{"play":"To Bolingbroke."},"64":{"play":"QUEEN: So, Green, thou art the midwife to my woe,"},"65":{"play":"And Bolingbroke my sorrow's dismal heir:"},"66":{"play":"Now hath my soul brought forth her prodigy,"},"67":{"play":"And I, a gasping new-deliver'd mother,"},"68":{"play":"Have woe to woe, sorrow to sorrow join'd."},"69":{"play":"BUSHY: Despair not, madam."},"70":{"play":"QUEEN: Who shall hinder me?"},"71":{"play":"I will despair, and be at enmity"},"72":{"play":"With cozening hope: he is a flatterer,"},"73":{"play":"A parasite, a keeper back of death,"},"74":{"play":"Who gently would dissolve the bands of life,"},"75":{"play":"Which false hope lingers in extremity."},"76":{"play":"GREEN: Here comes the Duke of York."},"77":{"play":"QUEEN: With signs of war about his aged neck:"},"78":{"play":"O, full of careful business are his looks!"},"79":{"play":"Uncle, for God's sake, speak comfortable words."},"80":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Should I do so, I should belie my thoughts:"},"81":{"play":"Comfort's in heaven; and we are on the earth,"},"82":{"play":"Where nothing lives but crosses, cares and grief."},"83":{"play":"Your husband, he is gone to save far off,"},"84":{"play":"Whilst others come to make him lose at home:"},"85":{"play":"Here am I left to underprop his land,"},"86":{"play":"Who, weak with age, cannot support myself:"},"87":{"play":"Now comes the sick hour that his surfeit made;"},"88":{"play":"Now shall he try his friends that flatter'd him."},"89":{"play":"He was? Why, so! go all which way it will!"},"90":{"play":"The nobles they are fled, the commons they are cold,"},"91":{"play":"And will, I fear, revolt on Hereford's side."},"92":{"play":"Sirrah, get thee to Plashy, to my sister Gloucester;"},"93":{"play":"Bid her send me presently a thousand pound:"},"94":{"play":"Hold, take my ring."},"95":{"play":"What is't, knave?"},"96":{"play":"God for his mercy! what a tide of woes"},"97":{"play":"Comes rushing on this woeful land at once!"},"98":{"play":"I know not what to do: I would to God,"},"99":{"play":"So my untruth had not provoked him to it,"},"100":{"play":"The king had cut off my head with my brother's."},"101":{"play":"What, are there no posts dispatch'd for Ireland?"},"102":{"play":"How shall we do for money for these wars?"},"103":{"play":"Come, sister,--cousin, I would say--pray, pardon me."},"104":{"play":"Go, fellow, get thee home, provide some carts"},"105":{"play":"And bring away the armour that is there."},"106":{"play":"Gentlemen, will you go muster men?"},"107":{"play":"If I know how or which way to order these affairs"},"108":{"play":"Thus thrust disorderly into my hands,"},"109":{"play":"Never believe me. Both are my kinsmen:"},"110":{"play":"The one is my sovereign, whom both my oath"},"111":{"play":"And duty bids defend; the other again"},"112":{"play":"Is my kinsman, whom the king hath wrong'd,"},"113":{"play":"Whom conscience and my kindred bids to right."},"114":{"play":"Well, somewhat we must do. Come, cousin, I'll"},"115":{"play":"Dispose of you."},"116":{"play":"Gentlemen, go, muster up your men,"},"117":{"play":"And meet me presently at Berkeley."},"118":{"play":"I should to Plashy too;"},"119":{"play":"But time will not permit: all is uneven,"},"120":{"play":"And every thing is left at six and seven."},"121":{"play":"BUSHY: The wind sits fair for news to go to Ireland,"},"122":{"play":"But none returns. For us to levy power"},"123":{"play":"Proportionable to the enemy"},"124":{"play":"Is all unpossible."},"125":{"play":"GREEN: Besides, our nearness to the king in love"},"126":{"play":"Is near the hate of those love not the king."},"127":{"play":"BAGOT: And that's the wavering commons: for their love"},"128":{"play":"Lies in their purses, and whoso empties them"},"129":{"play":"By so much fills their hearts with deadly hate."},"130":{"play":"BUSHY: Wherein the king stands generally condemn'd."},"131":{"play":"BAGOT: If judgement lie in them, then so do we,"},"132":{"play":"Because we ever have been near the king."},"133":{"play":"GREEN: Well, I will for refuge straight to Bristol castle:"},"134":{"play":"The Earl of Wiltshire is already there."},"135":{"play":"BUSHY: Thither will I with you; for little office"},"136":{"play":"The hateful commons will perform for us,"},"137":{"play":"Except like curs to tear us all to pieces."},"138":{"play":"Will you go along with us?"},"139":{"play":"BAGOT: No; I will to Ireland to his majesty."},"140":{"play":"Farewell: if heart's presages be not vain,"},"141":{"play":"We three here art that ne'er shall meet again."},"142":{"play":"BUSHY: That's as York thrives to beat back Bolingbroke."},"143":{"play":"GREEN: Alas, poor duke! the task he undertakes"},"144":{"play":"Is numbering sands and drinking oceans dry:"},"145":{"play":"Where one on his side fights, thousands will fly."},"146":{"play":"Farewell at once, for once, for all, and ever."},"147":{"play":"BUSHY: Well, we may meet again."},"148":{"play":"BAGOT: I fear me, never."}},"ACT 2 SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter HENRY BOLINGBROKE and NORTHUMBERLAND, with Forces]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: How far is it, my lord, to Berkeley now?"},"3":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Believe me, noble lord,"},"4":{"play":"I am a stranger here in Gloucestershire:"},"5":{"play":"These high wild hills and rough uneven ways"},"6":{"play":"Draws out our miles, and makes them wearisome,"},"7":{"play":"And yet your fair discourse hath been as sugar,"},"8":{"play":"Making the hard way sweet and delectable."},"9":{"play":"But I bethink me what a weary way"},"10":{"play":"From Ravenspurgh to Cotswold will be found"},"11":{"play":"In Ross and Willoughby, wanting your company,"},"12":{"play":"Which, I protest, hath very much beguiled"},"13":{"play":"The tediousness and process of my travel:"},"14":{"play":"But theirs is sweetened with the hope to have"},"15":{"play":"The present benefit which I possess;"},"16":{"play":"And hope to joy is little less in joy"},"17":{"play":"Than hope enjoy'd: by this the weary lords"},"18":{"play":"Shall make their way seem short, as mine hath done"},"19":{"play":"By sight of what I have, your noble company."},"20":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Of much less value is my company"},"21":{"play":"Than your good words. But who comes here?"},"22":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: It is my son, young Harry Percy,"},"23":{"play":"Sent from my brother Worcester, whencesoever."},"24":{"play":"Harry, how fares your uncle?"},"25":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: I had thought, my lord, to have learn'd his health of you."},"26":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Why, is he not with the queen?"},"27":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: No, my good Lord; he hath forsook the court,"},"28":{"play":"Broken his staff of office and dispersed"},"29":{"play":"The household of the king."},"30":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: What was his reason?"},"31":{"play":"He was not so resolved when last we spake together."},"32":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: Because your lordship was proclaimed traitor."},"33":{"play":"But he, my lord, is gone to Ravenspurgh,"},"34":{"play":"To offer service to the Duke of Hereford,"},"35":{"play":"And sent me over by Berkeley, to discover"},"36":{"play":"What power the Duke of York had levied there;"},"37":{"play":"Then with directions to repair to Ravenspurgh."},"38":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Have you forgot the Duke of Hereford, boy?"},"39":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: No, my good lord, for that is not forgot"},"40":{"play":"Which ne'er I did remember: to my knowledge,"},"41":{"play":"I never in my life did look on him."},"42":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Then learn to know him now; this is the duke."},"43":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: My gracious lord, I tender you my service,"},"44":{"play":"Such as it is, being tender, raw and young:"},"45":{"play":"Which elder days shall ripen and confirm"},"46":{"play":"To more approved service and desert."},"47":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I thank thee, gentle Percy; and be sure"},"48":{"play":"I count myself in nothing else so happy"},"49":{"play":"As in a soul remembering my good friends;"},"50":{"play":"And, as my fortune ripens with thy love,"},"51":{"play":"It shall be still thy true love's recompense:"},"52":{"play":"My heart this covenant makes, my hand thus seals it."},"53":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: How far is it to Berkeley? and what stir"},"54":{"play":"Keeps good old York there with his men of war?"},"55":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: There stands the castle, by yon tuft of trees,"},"56":{"play":"Mann'd with three hundred men, as I have heard;"},"57":{"play":"And in it are the Lords of York, Berkeley, and Seymour;"},"58":{"play":"None else of name and noble estimate."},"59":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Here come the Lords of Ross and Willoughby,"},"60":{"play":"Bloody with spurring, fiery-red with haste."},"61":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Welcome, my lords. I wot your love pursues"},"62":{"play":"A banish'd traitor: all my treasury"},"63":{"play":"Is yet but unfelt thanks, which more enrich'd"},"64":{"play":"Shall be your love and labour's recompense."},"65":{"play":"LORD ROSS: Your presence makes us rich, most noble lord."},"66":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: And far surmounts our labour to attain it."},"67":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Evermore thanks, the exchequer of the poor;"},"68":{"play":"Which, till my infant fortune comes to years,"},"69":{"play":"Stands for my bounty. But who comes here?"},"70":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: It is my Lord of Berkeley, as I guess."},"71":{"play":"LORD BERKELEY: My Lord of Hereford, my message is to you."},"72":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My lord, my answer is--to Lancaster;"},"73":{"play":"And I am come to seek that name in England;"},"74":{"play":"And I must find that title in your tongue,"},"75":{"play":"Before I make reply to aught you say."},"76":{"play":"LORD BERKELEY: Mistake me not, my lord; 'tis not my meaning"},"77":{"play":"To raze one title of your honour out:"},"78":{"play":"To you, my lord, I come, what lord you will,"},"79":{"play":"From the most gracious regent of this land,"},"80":{"play":"The Duke of York, to know what pricks you on"},"81":{"play":"To take advantage of the absent time"},"82":{"play":"And fright our native peace with self-born arms."},"83":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I shall not need transport my words by you;"},"84":{"play":"Here comes his grace in person. My noble uncle!"},"85":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Show me thy humble heart, and not thy knee,"},"86":{"play":"Whose duty is deceiveable and false."},"87":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My gracious uncle--"},"88":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Tut, tut!"},"89":{"play":"Grace me no grace, nor uncle me no uncle:"},"90":{"play":"I am no traitor's uncle; and that word 'grace.'"},"91":{"play":"In an ungracious mouth is but profane."},"92":{"play":"Why have those banish'd and forbidden legs"},"93":{"play":"Dared once to touch a dust of England's ground?"},"94":{"play":"But then more 'why?' why have they dared to march"},"95":{"play":"So many miles upon her peaceful bosom,"},"96":{"play":"Frighting her pale-faced villages with war"},"97":{"play":"And ostentation of despised arms?"},"98":{"play":"Comest thou because the anointed king is hence?"},"99":{"play":"Why, foolish boy, the king is left behind,"},"100":{"play":"And in my loyal bosom lies his power."},"101":{"play":"Were I but now the lord of such hot youth"},"102":{"play":"As when brave Gaunt, thy father, and myself"},"103":{"play":"Rescued the Black Prince, that young Mars of men,"},"104":{"play":"From forth the ranks of many thousand French,"},"105":{"play":"O, then how quickly should this arm of mine."},"106":{"play":"Now prisoner to the palsy, chastise thee"},"107":{"play":"And minister correction to thy fault!"},"108":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My gracious uncle, let me know my fault:"},"109":{"play":"On what condition stands it and wherein?"},"110":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Even in condition of the worst degree,"},"111":{"play":"In gross rebellion and detested treason:"},"112":{"play":"Thou art a banish'd man, and here art come"},"113":{"play":"Before the expiration of thy time,"},"114":{"play":"In braving arms against thy sovereign."},"115":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: As I was banish'd, I was banish'd Hereford;"},"116":{"play":"But as I come, I come for Lancaster."},"117":{"play":"And, noble uncle, I beseech your grace"},"118":{"play":"Look on my wrongs with an indifferent eye:"},"119":{"play":"You are my father, for methinks in you"},"120":{"play":"I see old Gaunt alive; O, then, my father,"},"121":{"play":"Will you permit that I shall stand condemn'd"},"122":{"play":"A wandering vagabond; my rights and royalties"},"123":{"play":"Pluck'd from my arms perforce and given away"},"124":{"play":"To upstart unthrifts? Wherefore was I born?"},"125":{"play":"If that my cousin king be King of England,"},"126":{"play":"It must be granted I am Duke of Lancaster."},"127":{"play":"You have a son, Aumerle, my noble cousin;"},"128":{"play":"Had you first died, and he been thus trod down,"},"129":{"play":"He should have found his uncle Gaunt a father,"},"130":{"play":"To rouse his wrongs and chase them to the bay."},"131":{"play":"I am denied to sue my livery here,"},"132":{"play":"And yet my letters-patents give me leave:"},"133":{"play":"My father's goods are all distrain'd and sold,"},"134":{"play":"And these and all are all amiss employ'd."},"135":{"play":"What would you have me do? I am a subject,"},"136":{"play":"And I challenge law: attorneys are denied me;"},"137":{"play":"And therefore, personally I lay my claim"},"138":{"play":"To my inheritance of free descent."},"139":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: The noble duke hath been too much abused."},"140":{"play":"LORD ROSS: It stands your grace upon to do him right."},"141":{"play":"LORD WILLOUGHBY: Base men by his endowments are made great."},"142":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: My lords of England, let me tell you this:"},"143":{"play":"I have had feeling of my cousin's wrongs"},"144":{"play":"And laboured all I could to do him right;"},"145":{"play":"But in this kind to come, in braving arms,"},"146":{"play":"Be his own carver and cut out his way,"},"147":{"play":"To find out right with wrong, it may not be;"},"148":{"play":"And you that do abet him in this kind"},"149":{"play":"Cherish rebellion and are rebels all."},"150":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: The noble duke hath sworn his coming is"},"151":{"play":"But for his own; and for the right of that"},"152":{"play":"We all have strongly sworn to give him aid;"},"153":{"play":"And let him ne'er see joy that breaks that oath!"},"154":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Well, well, I see the issue of these arms:"},"155":{"play":"I cannot mend it, I must needs confess,"},"156":{"play":"Because my power is weak and all ill left:"},"157":{"play":"But if I could, by Him that gave me life,"},"158":{"play":"I would attach you all and make you stoop"},"159":{"play":"Unto the sovereign mercy of the king;"},"160":{"play":"But since I cannot, be it known to you"},"161":{"play":"I do remain as neuter. So, fare you well;"},"162":{"play":"Unless you please to enter in the castle"},"163":{"play":"And there repose you for this night."},"164":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: An offer, uncle, that we will accept:"},"165":{"play":"But we must win your grace to go with us"},"166":{"play":"To Bristol castle, which they say is held"},"167":{"play":"By Bushy, Bagot and their complices,"},"168":{"play":"The caterpillars of the commonwealth,"},"169":{"play":"Which I have sworn to weed and pluck away."},"170":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: It may be I will go with you: but yet I'll pause;"},"171":{"play":"For I am loath to break our country's laws."},"172":{"play":"Nor friends nor foes, to me welcome you are:"},"173":{"play":"Things past redress are now with me past care."}},"ACT 2 SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Enter EARL OF SALISBURY and a Welsh Captain]"},"2":{"play":"EARL OF SALISBURY: Stay yet another day, thou trusty Welshman:"},"3":{"play":"The king reposeth all his confidence in thee."},"4":{"play":"[Exit]"},"5":{"play":"EARL OF SALISBURY: Ah, Richard, with the eyes of heavy mind"},"6":{"play":"I see thy glory like a shooting star"},"7":{"play":"Fall to the base earth from the firmament."},"8":{"play":"Thy sun sets weeping in the lowly west,"},"9":{"play":"Witnessing storms to come, woe and unrest:"},"10":{"play":"Thy friends are fled to wait upon thy foes,"},"11":{"play":"And crossly to thy good all fortune goes."},"12":{"play":"Shakespeare homepage"},"14":{"play":"Previous scene"},"15":{"play":"Next scene"}},"ACT 3 SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter HENRY BOLINGBROKE, DUKE OF YORK,  NORTHUMBERLAND, LORD ROSS, HENRY PERCY, LORD WILLOUGHBY, with BUSHY and GREEN, prisoners]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Bring forth these men."},"3":{"play":"Bushy and Green, I will not vex your souls--"},"4":{"play":"Since presently your souls must part your bodies--"},"5":{"play":"With too much urging your pernicious lives,"},"6":{"play":"For 'twere no charity; yet, to wash your blood"},"7":{"play":"From off my hands, here in the view of men"},"8":{"play":"I will unfold some causes of your deaths."},"9":{"play":"You have misled a prince, a royal king,"},"10":{"play":"A happy gentleman in blood and lineaments,"},"11":{"play":"By you unhappied and disfigured clean:"},"12":{"play":"You have in manner with your sinful hours"},"13":{"play":"Made a divorce betwixt his queen and him,"},"14":{"play":"Broke the possession of a royal bed"},"15":{"play":"And stain'd the beauty of a fair queen's cheeks"},"16":{"play":"With tears drawn from her eyes by your foul wrongs."},"17":{"play":"Myself, a prince by fortune of my birth,"},"18":{"play":"Near to the king in blood, and near in love"},"19":{"play":"Till you did make him misinterpret me,"},"20":{"play":"Have stoop'd my neck under your injuries,"},"21":{"play":"And sigh'd my English breath in foreign clouds,"},"22":{"play":"Eating the bitter bread of banishment;"},"23":{"play":"Whilst you have fed upon my signories,"},"24":{"play":"Dispark'd my parks and fell'd my forest woods,"},"25":{"play":"From my own windows torn my household coat,"},"26":{"play":"Razed out my imprese, leaving me no sign,"},"27":{"play":"Save men's opinions and my living blood,"},"28":{"play":"To show the world I am a gentleman."},"29":{"play":"This and much more, much more than twice all this,"},"30":{"play":"Condemns you to the death. See them deliver'd over"},"31":{"play":"To execution and the hand of death."},"32":{"play":"BUSHY: More welcome is the stroke of death to me"},"33":{"play":"Than Bolingbroke to England. Lords, farewell."},"34":{"play":"GREEN: My comfort is that heaven will take our souls"},"35":{"play":"And plague injustice with the pains of hell."},"36":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My Lord Northumberland, see them dispatch'd."},"37":{"play":"Uncle, you say the queen is at your house;"},"38":{"play":"For God's sake, fairly let her be entreated:"},"39":{"play":"Tell her I send to her my kind commends;"},"40":{"play":"Take special care my greetings be deliver'd."},"41":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: A gentleman of mine I have dispatch'd"},"42":{"play":"With letters of your love to her at large."},"43":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Thank, gentle uncle. Come, lords, away."},"44":{"play":"To fight with Glendower and his complices:"},"45":{"play":"Awhile to work, and after holiday."}},"ACT 3 SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Barkloughly castle call they this at hand?"},"2":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Yea, my lord. How brooks your grace the air,"},"3":{"play":"After your late tossing on the breaking seas?"},"4":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Needs must I like it well: I weep for joy"},"5":{"play":"To stand upon my kingdom once again."},"6":{"play":"Dear earth, I do salute thee with my hand,"},"7":{"play":"Though rebels wound thee with their horses' hoofs:"},"8":{"play":"As a long-parted mother with her child"},"9":{"play":"Plays fondly with her tears and smiles in meeting,"},"10":{"play":"So, weeping, smiling, greet I thee, my earth,"},"11":{"play":"And do thee favours with my royal hands."},"12":{"play":"Feed not thy sovereign's foe, my gentle earth,"},"13":{"play":"Nor with thy sweets comfort his ravenous sense;"},"14":{"play":"But let thy spiders, that suck up thy venom,"},"15":{"play":"And heavy-gaited toads lie in their way,"},"16":{"play":"Doing annoyance to the treacherous feet"},"17":{"play":"Which with usurping steps do trample thee:"},"18":{"play":"Yield stinging nettles to mine enemies;"},"19":{"play":"And when they from thy bosom pluck a flower,"},"20":{"play":"Guard it, I pray thee, with a lurking adder"},"21":{"play":"Whose double tongue may with a mortal touch"},"22":{"play":"Throw death upon thy sovereign's enemies."},"23":{"play":"Mock not my senseless conjuration, lords:"},"24":{"play":"This earth shall have a feeling and these stones"},"25":{"play":"Prove armed soldiers, ere her native king"},"26":{"play":"Shall falter under foul rebellion's arms."},"27":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: Fear not, my lord: that Power that made you king"},"28":{"play":"Hath power to keep you king in spite of all."},"29":{"play":"The means that heaven yields must be embraced,"},"30":{"play":"And not neglected; else, if heaven would,"},"31":{"play":"And we will not, heaven's offer we refuse,"},"32":{"play":"The proffer'd means of succor and redress."},"33":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: He means, my lord, that we are too remiss;"},"34":{"play":"Whilst Bolingbroke, through our security,"},"35":{"play":"Grows strong and great in substance and in power."},"36":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Discomfortable cousin! know'st thou not"},"37":{"play":"That when the searching eye of heaven is hid,"},"38":{"play":"Behind the globe, that lights the lower world,"},"39":{"play":"Then thieves and robbers range abroad unseen"},"40":{"play":"In murders and in outrage, boldly here;"},"41":{"play":"But when from under this terrestrial ball"},"42":{"play":"He fires the proud tops of the eastern pines"},"43":{"play":"And darts his light through every guilty hole,"},"44":{"play":"Then murders, treasons and detested sins,"},"45":{"play":"The cloak of night being pluck'd from off their backs,"},"46":{"play":"Stand bare and naked, trembling at themselves?"},"47":{"play":"So when this thief, this traitor, Bolingbroke,"},"48":{"play":"Who all this while hath revell'd in the night"},"49":{"play":"Whilst we were wandering with the antipodes,"},"50":{"play":"Shall see us rising in our throne, the east,"},"51":{"play":"His treasons will sit blushing in his face,"},"52":{"play":"Not able to endure the sight of day,"},"53":{"play":"But self-affrighted tremble at his sin."},"54":{"play":"Not all the water in the rough rude sea"},"55":{"play":"Can wash the balm off from an anointed king;"},"56":{"play":"The breath of worldly men cannot depose"},"57":{"play":"The deputy elected by the Lord:"},"58":{"play":"For every man that Bolingbroke hath press'd"},"59":{"play":"To lift shrewd steel against our golden crown,"},"60":{"play":"God for his Richard hath in heavenly pay"},"61":{"play":"A glorious angel: then, if angels fight,"},"62":{"play":"Weak men must fall, for heaven still guards the right."},"63":{"play":"Welcome, my lord\thow far off lies your power?"},"64":{"play":"EARL OF SALISBURY: Nor near nor farther off, my gracious lord,"},"65":{"play":"Than this weak arm: discomfort guides my tongue"},"66":{"play":"And bids me speak of nothing but despair."},"67":{"play":"One day too late, I fear me, noble lord,"},"68":{"play":"Hath clouded all thy happy days on earth:"},"69":{"play":"O, call back yesterday, bid time return,"},"70":{"play":"And thou shalt have twelve thousand fighting men!"},"71":{"play":"To-day, to-day, unhappy day, too late,"},"72":{"play":"O'erthrows thy joys, friends, fortune and thy state:"},"73":{"play":"For all the Welshmen, hearing thou wert dead."},"74":{"play":"Are gone to Bolingbroke, dispersed and fled."},"75":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Comfort, my liege; why looks your grace so pale?"},"76":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: But now the blood of twenty thousand men"},"77":{"play":"Did triumph in my face, and they are fled;"},"78":{"play":"And, till so much blood thither come again,"},"79":{"play":"Have I not reason to look pale and dead?"},"80":{"play":"All souls that will be safe fly from my side,"},"81":{"play":"For time hath set a blot upon my pride."},"82":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Comfort, my liege; remember who you are."},"83":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: I had forgot myself; am I not king?"},"84":{"play":"Awake, thou coward majesty! thou sleepest."},"85":{"play":"Is not the king's name twenty thousand names?"},"86":{"play":"Arm, arm, my name! a puny subject strikes"},"87":{"play":"At thy great glory. Look not to the ground,"},"88":{"play":"Ye favourites of a king: are we not high?"},"89":{"play":"High be our thoughts: I know my uncle York"},"90":{"play":"Hath power enough to serve our turn. But who comes here?"},"91":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: More health and happiness betide my liege"},"92":{"play":"Than can my care-tuned tongue deliver him!"},"93":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Mine ear is open and my heart prepared;"},"94":{"play":"The worst is worldly loss thou canst unfold."},"95":{"play":"Say, is my kingdom lost? why, 'twas my care"},"96":{"play":"And what loss is it to be rid of care?"},"97":{"play":"Strives Bolingbroke to be as great as we?"},"98":{"play":"Greater he shall not be; if he serve God,"},"99":{"play":"We'll serve Him too and be his fellow so:"},"100":{"play":"Revolt our subjects? that we cannot mend;"},"101":{"play":"They break their faith to God as well as us:"},"102":{"play":"Cry woe, destruction, ruin and decay:"},"103":{"play":"The worst is death, and death will have his day."},"104":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: Glad am I that your highness is so arm'd"},"105":{"play":"To bear the tidings of calamity."},"106":{"play":"Like an unseasonable stormy day,"},"107":{"play":"Which makes the silver rivers drown their shores,"},"108":{"play":"As if the world were all dissolved to tears,"},"109":{"play":"So high above his limits swells the rage"},"110":{"play":"Of Bolingbroke, covering your fearful land"},"111":{"play":"With hard bright steel and hearts harder than steel."},"112":{"play":"White-beards have arm'd their thin and hairless scalps"},"113":{"play":"Against thy majesty; boys, with women's voices,"},"114":{"play":"Strive to speak big and clap their female joints"},"115":{"play":"In stiff unwieldy arms against thy crown:"},"116":{"play":"The very beadsmen learn to bend their bows"},"117":{"play":"Of double-fatal yew against thy state;"},"118":{"play":"Yea, distaff-women manage rusty bills"},"119":{"play":"Against thy seat: both young and old rebel,"},"120":{"play":"And all goes worse than I have power to tell."},"121":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Too well, too well thou tell'st a tale so ill."},"122":{"play":"Where is the Earl of Wiltshire? where is Bagot?"},"123":{"play":"What is become of Bushy? where is Green?"},"124":{"play":"That they have let the dangerous enemy"},"125":{"play":"Measure our confines with such peaceful steps?"},"126":{"play":"If we prevail, their heads shall pay for it:"},"127":{"play":"I warrant they have made peace with Bolingbroke."},"128":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: Peace have they made with him indeed, my lord."},"129":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: O villains, vipers, damn'd without redemption!"},"130":{"play":"Dogs, easily won to fawn on any man!"},"131":{"play":"Snakes, in my heart-blood warm'd, that sting my heart!"},"132":{"play":"Three Judases, each one thrice worse than Judas!"},"133":{"play":"Would they make peace? terrible hell make war"},"134":{"play":"Upon their spotted souls for this offence!"},"135":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: Sweet love, I see, changing his property,"},"136":{"play":"Turns to the sourest and most deadly hate:"},"137":{"play":"Again uncurse their souls; their peace is made"},"138":{"play":"With heads, and not with hands; those whom you curse"},"139":{"play":"Have felt the worst of death's destroying wound"},"140":{"play":"And lie full low, graved in the hollow ground."},"141":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Is Bushy, Green, and the Earl of Wiltshire dead?"},"142":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: Ay, all of them at Bristol lost their heads."},"143":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Where is the duke my father with his power?"},"144":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: No matter where; of comfort no man speak:"},"145":{"play":"Let's talk of graves, of worms, and epitaphs;"},"146":{"play":"Make dust our paper and with rainy eyes"},"147":{"play":"Write sorrow on the bosom of the earth,"},"148":{"play":"Let's choose executors and talk of wills:"},"149":{"play":"And yet not so, for what can we bequeath"},"150":{"play":"Save our deposed bodies to the ground?"},"151":{"play":"Our lands, our lives and all are Bolingbroke's,"},"152":{"play":"And nothing can we call our own but death"},"153":{"play":"And that small model of the barren earth"},"154":{"play":"Which serves as paste and cover to our bones."},"155":{"play":"For God's sake, let us sit upon the ground"},"156":{"play":"And tell sad stories of the death of kings;"},"157":{"play":"How some have been deposed; some slain in war,"},"158":{"play":"Some haunted by the ghosts they have deposed;"},"159":{"play":"Some poison'd by their wives: some sleeping kill'd;"},"160":{"play":"All murder'd: for within the hollow crown"},"161":{"play":"That rounds the mortal temples of a king"},"162":{"play":"Keeps Death his court and there the antic sits,"},"163":{"play":"Scoffing his state and grinning at his pomp,"},"164":{"play":"Allowing him a breath, a little scene,"},"165":{"play":"To monarchize, be fear'd and kill with looks,"},"166":{"play":"Infusing him with self and vain conceit,"},"167":{"play":"As if this flesh which walls about our life,"},"168":{"play":"Were brass impregnable, and humour'd thus"},"169":{"play":"Comes at the last and with a little pin"},"170":{"play":"Bores through his castle wall, and farewell king!"},"171":{"play":"Cover your heads and mock not flesh and blood"},"172":{"play":"With solemn reverence: throw away respect,"},"173":{"play":"Tradition, form and ceremonious duty,"},"174":{"play":"For you have but mistook me all this while:"},"175":{"play":"I live with bread like you, feel want,"},"176":{"play":"Taste grief, need friends: subjected thus,"},"177":{"play":"How can you say to me, I am a king?"},"178":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: My lord, wise men ne'er sit and wail their woes,"},"179":{"play":"But presently prevent the ways to wail."},"180":{"play":"To fear the foe, since fear oppresseth strength,"},"181":{"play":"Gives in your weakness strength unto your foe,"},"182":{"play":"And so your follies fight against yourself."},"183":{"play":"Fear and be slain; no worse can come to fight:"},"184":{"play":"And fight and die is death destroying death;"},"185":{"play":"Where fearing dying pays death servile breath."},"186":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: My father hath a power; inquire of him"},"187":{"play":"And learn to make a body of a limb."},"188":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Thou chidest me well: proud Bolingbroke, I come"},"189":{"play":"To change blows with thee for our day of doom."},"190":{"play":"This ague fit of fear is over-blown;"},"191":{"play":"An easy task it is to win our own."},"192":{"play":"Say, Scroop, where lies our uncle with his power?"},"193":{"play":"Speak sweetly, man, although thy looks be sour."},"194":{"play":"SIR STEPHEN SCROOP: Men judge by the complexion of the sky"},"195":{"play":"The state and inclination of the day:"},"196":{"play":"So may you by my dull and heavy eye,"},"197":{"play":"My tongue hath but a heavier tale to say."},"198":{"play":"I play the torturer, by small and small"},"199":{"play":"To lengthen out the worst that must be spoken:"},"200":{"play":"Your uncle York is join'd with Bolingbroke,"},"201":{"play":"And all your northern castles yielded up,"},"202":{"play":"And all your southern gentlemen in arms"},"203":{"play":"Upon his party."},"204":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Thou hast said enough."},"205":{"play":"Beshrew thee, cousin, which didst lead me forth"},"206":{"play":"Of that sweet way I was in to despair!"},"207":{"play":"What say you now? what comfort have we now?"},"208":{"play":"By heaven, I'll hate him everlastingly"},"209":{"play":"That bids me be of comfort any more."},"210":{"play":"Go to Flint castle: there I'll pine away;"},"211":{"play":"A king, woe's slave, shall kingly woe obey."},"212":{"play":"That power I have, discharge; and let them go"},"213":{"play":"To ear the land that hath some hope to grow,"},"214":{"play":"For I have none: let no man speak again"},"215":{"play":"To alter this, for counsel is but vain."},"216":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: My liege, one word."},"217":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: He does me double wrong"},"218":{"play":"That wounds me with the flatteries of his tongue."},"219":{"play":"Discharge my followers: let them hence away,"},"220":{"play":"From Richard's night to Bolingbroke's fair day."}},"ACT 3 SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter, with drum and colours, HENRY BOLINGBROKE, DUKE OF YORK, NORTHUMBERLAND, Attendants, and forces]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: So that by this intelligence we learn"},"3":{"play":"The Welshmen are dispersed, and Salisbury"},"4":{"play":"Is gone to meet the king, who lately landed"},"5":{"play":"With some few private friends upon this coast."},"6":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: The news is very fair and good, my lord:"},"7":{"play":"Richard not far from hence hath hid his head."},"8":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: It would beseem the Lord Northumberland"},"9":{"play":"To say 'King Richard:' alack the heavy day"},"10":{"play":"When such a sacred king should hide his head."},"11":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Your grace mistakes; only to be brief"},"12":{"play":"Left I his title out."},"13":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: The time hath been,"},"14":{"play":"Would you have been so brief with him, he would"},"15":{"play":"Have been so brief with you, to shorten you,"},"16":{"play":"For taking so the head, your whole head's length."},"17":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Mistake not, uncle, further than you should."},"18":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Take not, good cousin, further than you should."},"19":{"play":"Lest you mistake the heavens are o'er our heads."},"20":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I know it, uncle, and oppose not myself"},"21":{"play":"Against their will. But who comes here?"},"22":{"play":"Welcome, Harry: what, will not this castle yield?"},"23":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: The castle royally is mann'd, my lord,"},"24":{"play":"Against thy entrance."},"25":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Royally!"},"26":{"play":"Why, it contains no king?"},"27":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: Yes, my good lord,"},"28":{"play":"It doth contain a king; King Richard lies"},"29":{"play":"Within the limits of yon lime and stone:"},"30":{"play":"And with him are the Lord Aumerle, Lord Salisbury,"},"31":{"play":"Sir Stephen Scroop, besides a clergyman"},"32":{"play":"Of holy reverence; who, I cannot learn."},"33":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: O, belike it is the Bishop of Carlisle."},"34":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Noble lords,"},"35":{"play":"Go to the rude ribs of that ancient castle;"},"36":{"play":"Through brazen trumpet send the breath of parley"},"37":{"play":"Into his ruin'd ears, and thus deliver:"},"38":{"play":"Henry Bolingbroke"},"39":{"play":"On both his knees doth kiss King Richard's hand"},"40":{"play":"And sends allegiance and true faith of heart"},"41":{"play":"To his most royal person, hither come"},"42":{"play":"Even at his feet to lay my arms and power,"},"43":{"play":"Provided that my banishment repeal'd"},"44":{"play":"And lands restored again be freely granted:"},"45":{"play":"If not, I'll use the advantage of my power"},"46":{"play":"And lay the summer's dust with showers of blood"},"47":{"play":"Rain'd from the wounds of slaughter'd Englishmen:"},"48":{"play":"The which, how far off from the mind of Bolingbroke"},"49":{"play":"It is, such crimson tempest should bedrench"},"50":{"play":"The fresh green lap of fair King Richard's land,"},"51":{"play":"My stooping duty tenderly shall show."},"52":{"play":"Go, signify as much, while here we march"},"53":{"play":"Upon the grassy carpet of this plain."},"54":{"play":"Let's march without the noise of threatening drum,"},"55":{"play":"That from this castle's tatter'd battlements"},"56":{"play":"Our fair appointments may be well perused."},"57":{"play":"Methinks King Richard and myself should meet"},"58":{"play":"With no less terror than the elements"},"59":{"play":"Of fire and water, when their thundering shock"},"60":{"play":"At meeting tears the cloudy cheeks of heaven."},"61":{"play":"Be he the fire, I'll be the yielding water:"},"62":{"play":"The rage be his, whilst on the earth I rain"},"63":{"play":"My waters; on the earth, and not on him."},"64":{"play":"March on, and mark King Richard how he looks."},"65":{"play":"See, see, King Richard doth himself appear,"},"66":{"play":"As doth the blushing discontented sun"},"67":{"play":"From out the fiery portal of the east,"},"68":{"play":"When he perceives the envious clouds are bent"},"69":{"play":"To dim his glory and to stain the track"},"70":{"play":"Of his bright passage to the occident."},"71":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Yet looks he like a king: behold, his eye,"},"72":{"play":"As bright as is the eagle's, lightens forth"},"73":{"play":"Controlling majesty: alack, alack, for woe,"},"74":{"play":"That any harm should stain so fair a show!"},"75":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We are amazed; and thus long have we stood"},"76":{"play":"To watch the fearful bending of thy knee,"},"77":{"play":"Because we thought ourself thy lawful king:"},"78":{"play":"And if we be, how dare thy joints forget"},"79":{"play":"To pay their awful duty to our presence?"},"80":{"play":"If we be not, show us the hand of God"},"81":{"play":"That hath dismissed us from our stewardship;"},"82":{"play":"For well we know, no hand of blood and bone"},"83":{"play":"Can gripe the sacred handle of our sceptre,"},"84":{"play":"Unless he do profane, steal, or usurp."},"85":{"play":"And though you think that all, as you have done,"},"86":{"play":"Have torn their souls by turning them from us,"},"87":{"play":"And we are barren and bereft of friends;"},"88":{"play":"Yet know, my master, God omnipotent,"},"89":{"play":"Is mustering in his clouds on our behalf"},"90":{"play":"Armies of pestilence; and they shall strike"},"91":{"play":"Your children yet unborn and unbegot,"},"92":{"play":"That lift your vassal hands against my head"},"93":{"play":"And threat the glory of my precious crown."},"94":{"play":"Tell Bolingbroke--for yond methinks he stands--"},"95":{"play":"That every stride he makes upon my land"},"96":{"play":"Is dangerous treason: he is come to open"},"97":{"play":"The purple testament of bleeding war;"},"98":{"play":"But ere the crown he looks for live in peace,"},"99":{"play":"Ten thousand bloody crowns of mothers' sons"},"100":{"play":"Shall ill become the flower of England's face,"},"101":{"play":"Change the complexion of her maid-pale peace"},"102":{"play":"To scarlet indignation and bedew"},"103":{"play":"Her pastures' grass with faithful English blood."},"104":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: The king of heaven forbid our lord the king"},"105":{"play":"Should so with civil and uncivil arms"},"106":{"play":"Be rush'd upon! Thy thrice noble cousin"},"107":{"play":"Harry Bolingbroke doth humbly kiss thy hand;"},"108":{"play":"And by the honourable tomb he swears,"},"109":{"play":"That stands upon your royal grandsire's bones,"},"110":{"play":"And by the royalties of both your bloods,"},"111":{"play":"Currents that spring from one most gracious head,"},"112":{"play":"And by the buried hand of warlike Gaunt,"},"113":{"play":"And by the worth and honour of himself,"},"114":{"play":"Comprising all that may be sworn or said,"},"115":{"play":"His coming hither hath no further scope"},"116":{"play":"Than for his lineal royalties and to beg"},"117":{"play":"Enfranchisement immediate on his kn ees:"},"118":{"play":"Which on thy royal party granted once,"},"119":{"play":"His glittering arms he will commend to rust,"},"120":{"play":"His barbed steeds to stables, and his heart"},"121":{"play":"To faithful service of your majesty."},"122":{"play":"This swears he, as he is a prince, is just;"},"123":{"play":"And, as I am a gentleman, I credit him."},"124":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Northumberland, say thus the king returns:"},"125":{"play":"His noble cousin is right welcome hither;"},"126":{"play":"And all the number of his fair demands"},"127":{"play":"Shall be accomplish'd without contradiction:"},"128":{"play":"With all the gracious utterance thou hast"},"129":{"play":"Speak to his gentle hearing kind commends."},"130":{"play":"We do debase ourselves, cousin, do we not,"},"131":{"play":"To look so poorly and to speak so fair?"},"132":{"play":"Shall we call back Northumberland, and send"},"133":{"play":"Defiance to the traitor, and so die?"},"134":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: No, good my lord; let's fight with gentle words"},"135":{"play":"Till time lend friends and friends their helpful swords."},"136":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: O God, O God! that e'er this tongue of mine,"},"137":{"play":"That laid the sentence of dread banishment"},"138":{"play":"On yon proud man, should take it off again"},"139":{"play":"With words of sooth! O that I were as great"},"140":{"play":"As is my grief, or lesser than my name!"},"141":{"play":"Or that I could forget what I have been,"},"142":{"play":"Or not remember what I must be now!"},"143":{"play":"Swell'st thou, proud heart? I'll give thee scope to beat,"},"144":{"play":"Since foes have scope to beat both thee and me."},"145":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Northumberland comes back from Bolingbroke."},"146":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: What must the king do now? must he submit?"},"147":{"play":"The king shall do it: must he be deposed?"},"148":{"play":"The king shall be contented: must he lose"},"149":{"play":"The name of king? o' God's name, let it go:"},"150":{"play":"I'll give my jewels for a set of beads,"},"151":{"play":"My gorgeous palace for a hermitage,"},"152":{"play":"My gay apparel for an almsman's gown,"},"153":{"play":"My figured goblets for a dish of wood,"},"154":{"play":"My sceptre for a palmer's walking staff,"},"155":{"play":"My subjects for a pair of carved saints"},"156":{"play":"And my large kingdom for a little grave,"},"157":{"play":"A little little grave, an obscure grave;"},"158":{"play":"Or I'll be buried in the king's highway,"},"159":{"play":"Some way of common trade, where subjects' feet"},"160":{"play":"May hourly trample on their sovereign's head;"},"161":{"play":"For on my heart they tread now whilst I live;"},"162":{"play":"And buried once, why not upon my head?"},"163":{"play":"Aumerle, thou weep'st, my tender-hearted cousin!"},"164":{"play":"We'll make foul weather with despised tears;"},"165":{"play":"Our sighs and they shall lodge the summer corn,"},"166":{"play":"And make a dearth in this revolting land."},"167":{"play":"Or shall we play the wantons with our woes,"},"168":{"play":"And make some pretty match with shedding tears?"},"169":{"play":"As thus, to drop them still upon one place,"},"170":{"play":"Till they have fretted us a pair of graves"},"171":{"play":"Within the earth; and, therein laid,--there lies"},"172":{"play":"Two kinsmen digg'd their graves with weeping eyes."},"173":{"play":"Would not this ill do well? Well, well, I see"},"174":{"play":"I talk but idly, and you laugh at me."},"175":{"play":"Most mighty prince, my Lord Northumberland,"},"176":{"play":"What says King Bolingbroke? will his majesty"},"177":{"play":"Give Richard leave to live till Richard die?"},"178":{"play":"You make a leg, and Bolingbroke says ay."},"179":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My lord, in the base court he doth attend"},"180":{"play":"To speak with you; may it please you to come down."},"181":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Down, down I come; like glistering Phaethon,"},"182":{"play":"Wanting the manage of unruly jades."},"183":{"play":"In the base court? Base court, where kings grow base,"},"184":{"play":"To come at traitors' calls and do them grace."},"185":{"play":"In the base court? Come down? Down, court!"},"186":{"play":"down, king!"},"187":{"play":"For night-owls shriek where mounting larks"},"188":{"play":"should sing."},"189":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: What says his majesty?"},"190":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Sorrow and grief of heart"},"191":{"play":"Makes him speak fondly, like a frantic man"},"192":{"play":"Yet he is come."},"193":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Stand all apart,"},"194":{"play":"And show fair duty to his majesty."},"195":{"play":"My gracious lord,--"},"196":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Fair cousin, you debase your princely knee"},"197":{"play":"To make the base earth proud with kissing it:"},"198":{"play":"Me rather had my heart might feel your love"},"199":{"play":"Than my unpleased eye see your courtesy."},"200":{"play":"Up, cousin, up; your heart is up, I know,"},"201":{"play":"Thus high at least, although your knee be low."},"202":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: My gracious lord, I come but for mine own."},"203":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Your own is yours, and I am yours, and all."},"204":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: So far be mine, my most redoubted lord,"},"205":{"play":"As my true service shall deserve your love."},"206":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Well you deserve: they well deserve to have,"},"207":{"play":"That know the strong'st and surest way to get."},"208":{"play":"Uncle, give me your hands: nay, dry your eyes;"},"209":{"play":"Tears show their love, but want their remedies."},"210":{"play":"Cousin, I am too young to be your father,"},"211":{"play":"Though you are old enough to be my heir."},"212":{"play":"What you will have, I'll give, and willing too;"},"213":{"play":"For do we must what force will have us do."},"214":{"play":"Set on towards London, cousin, is it so?"},"215":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Yea, my good lord."},"216":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Then I must not say no."}},"ACT 3 SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Enter the QUEEN and two Ladies]"},"2":{"play":"QUEEN: What sport shall we devise here in this garden,"},"3":{"play":"To drive away the heavy thought of care?"},"4":{"play":"'Twill make me think the world is full of rubs,"},"5":{"play":"And that my fortune rubs against the bias."},"6":{"play":"My legs can keep no measure in delight,"},"7":{"play":"When my poor heart no measure keeps in grief:"},"8":{"play":"Therefore, no dancing, girl; some other sport."},"9":{"play":"Of sorrow or of joy?"},"10":{"play":"Of neither, girl:"},"11":{"play":"For of joy, being altogether wanting,"},"12":{"play":"It doth remember me the more of sorrow;"},"13":{"play":"Or if of grief, being altogether had,"},"14":{"play":"It adds more sorrow to my want of joy:"},"15":{"play":"For what I have I need not to repeat;"},"16":{"play":"And what I want it boots not to complain."},"17":{"play":"'Tis well that thou hast cause"},"18":{"play":"But thou shouldst please me better, wouldst thou weep."},"19":{"play":"And I could sing, would weeping do me good,"},"20":{"play":"And never borrow any tear of thee."},"21":{"play":"But stay, here come the gardeners:"},"22":{"play":"Let's step into the shadow of these trees."},"23":{"play":"My wretchedness unto a row of pins,"},"24":{"play":"They'll talk of state; for every one doth so"},"25":{"play":"Against a change; woe is forerun with woe."},"26":{"play":"O, I am press'd to death through want of speaking!"},"27":{"play":"Thou, old Adam's likeness, set to dress this garden,"},"28":{"play":"How dares thy harsh rude tongue sound this unpleasing news?"},"29":{"play":"What Eve, what serpent, hath suggested thee"},"30":{"play":"To make a second fall of cursed man?"},"31":{"play":"Why dost thou say King Richard is deposed?"},"32":{"play":"Darest thou, thou little better thing than earth,"},"33":{"play":"Divine his downfall? Say, where, when, and how,"},"34":{"play":"Camest thou by this ill tidings? speak, thou wretch."},"35":{"play":"Nimble mischance, that art so light of foot,"},"36":{"play":"Doth not thy embassage belong to me,"},"37":{"play":"And am I last that knows it? O, thou think'st"},"38":{"play":"To serve me last, that I may longest keep"},"39":{"play":"Thy sorrow in my breast. Come, ladies, go,"},"40":{"play":"To meet at London London's king in woe."},"41":{"play":"What, was I born to this, that my sad look"},"42":{"play":"Should grace the triumph of great Bolingbroke?"},"43":{"play":"Gardener, for telling me these news of woe,"},"44":{"play":"Pray God the plants thou graft'st may never grow."},"45":{"play":"GARDENER: Poor queen! so that thy state might be no worse,"},"46":{"play":"I would my skill were subject to thy curse."},"47":{"play":"Here did she fall a tear; here in this place"},"48":{"play":"I'll set a bank of rue, sour herb of grace:"},"49":{"play":"Rue, even for ruth, here shortly shall be seen,"},"50":{"play":"In the remembrance of a weeping queen."},"51":{"play":"Shakespeare homepage"},"53":{"play":"Previous scene"},"54":{"play":"Next scene"}},"ACT 4 SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter, as to the Parliament, HENRY BOLINGBROKE,  DUKE OF AUMERLE, NORTHUMBERLAND, HENRY PERCY, LORD  FITZWATER, DUKE OF SURREY, the BISHOP OF CARLISLE,  the Abbot Of Westminster, and another Lord, Herald, Officers, and BAGOT]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Call forth Bagot."},"3":{"play":"Now, Bagot, freely speak thy mind;"},"4":{"play":"What thou dost know of noble Gloucester's death,"},"5":{"play":"Who wrought it with the king, and who perform'd"},"6":{"play":"The bloody office of his timeless end."},"7":{"play":"BAGOT: Then set before my face the Lord Aumerle."},"8":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Cousin, stand forth, and look upon that man."},"9":{"play":"BAGOT: My Lord Aumerle, I know your daring tongue"},"10":{"play":"Scorns to unsay what once it hath deliver'd."},"11":{"play":"In that dead time when Gloucester's death was plotted,"},"12":{"play":"I heard you say, 'Is not my arm of length,"},"13":{"play":"That reacheth from the restful English court"},"14":{"play":"As far as Calais, to mine uncle's head?'"},"15":{"play":"Amongst much other talk, that very time,"},"16":{"play":"I heard you say that you had rather refuse"},"17":{"play":"The offer of an hundred thousand crowns"},"18":{"play":"Than Bolingbroke's return to England;"},"19":{"play":"Adding withal how blest this land would be"},"20":{"play":"In this your cousin's death."},"21":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Princes and noble lords,"},"22":{"play":"What answer shall I make to this base man?"},"23":{"play":"Shall I so much dishonour my fair stars,"},"24":{"play":"On equal terms to give him chastisement?"},"25":{"play":"Either I must, or have mine honour soil'd"},"26":{"play":"With the attainder of his slanderous lips."},"27":{"play":"There is my gage, the manual seal of death,"},"28":{"play":"That marks thee out for hell: I say, thou liest,"},"29":{"play":"And will maintain what thou hast said is false"},"30":{"play":"In thy heart-blood, though being all too base"},"31":{"play":"To stain the temper of my knightly sword."},"32":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Bagot, forbear; thou shalt not take it up."},"33":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Excepting one, I would he were the best"},"34":{"play":"In all this presence that hath moved me so."},"35":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: If that thy valour stand on sympathy,"},"36":{"play":"There is my gage, Aumerle, in gage to thine:"},"37":{"play":"By that fair sun which shows me where thou stand'st,"},"38":{"play":"I heard thee say, and vauntingly thou spakest it"},"39":{"play":"That thou wert cause of noble Gloucester's death."},"40":{"play":"If thou deny'st it twenty times, thou liest;"},"41":{"play":"And I will turn thy falsehood to thy heart,"},"42":{"play":"Where it was forged, with my rapier's point."},"43":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Thou darest not, coward, live to see that day."},"44":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: Now by my soul, I would it were this hour."},"45":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Fitzwater, thou art damn'd to hell for this."},"46":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: Aumerle, thou liest; his honour is as true"},"47":{"play":"In this appeal as thou art all unjust;"},"48":{"play":"And that thou art so, there I throw my gage,"},"49":{"play":"To prove it on thee to the extremest point"},"50":{"play":"Of mortal breathing: seize it, if thou darest."},"51":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: An if I do not, may my hands rot off"},"52":{"play":"And never brandish more revengeful steel"},"53":{"play":"Over the glittering helmet of my foe!"},"54":{"play":"Who sets me else? by heaven, I'll throw at all:"},"55":{"play":"I have a thousand spirits in one breast,"},"56":{"play":"To answer twenty thousand such as you."},"57":{"play":"DUKE OF SURREY: My Lord Fitzwater, I do remember well"},"58":{"play":"The very time Aumerle and you did talk."},"59":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: 'Tis very true: you were in presence then;"},"60":{"play":"And you can witness with me this is true."},"61":{"play":"DUKE OF SURREY: As false, by heaven, as heaven itself is true."},"62":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: Surrey, thou liest."},"63":{"play":"DUKE OF SURREY: Dishonourable boy!"},"64":{"play":"That lie shall lie so heavy on my sword,"},"65":{"play":"That it shall render vengeance and revenge"},"66":{"play":"Till thou the lie-giver and that lie do lie"},"67":{"play":"In earth as quiet as thy father's skull:"},"68":{"play":"In proof whereof, there is my honour's pawn;"},"69":{"play":"Engage it to the trial, if thou darest."},"70":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: How fondly dost thou spur a forward horse!"},"71":{"play":"If I dare eat, or drink, or breathe, or live,"},"72":{"play":"I dare meet Surrey in a wilderness,"},"73":{"play":"And spit upon him, whilst I say he lies,"},"74":{"play":"And lies, and lies: there is my bond of faith,"},"75":{"play":"To tie thee to my strong correction."},"76":{"play":"As I intend to thrive in this new world,"},"77":{"play":"Aumerle is guilty of my true appeal:"},"78":{"play":"Besides, I heard the banish'd Norfolk say"},"79":{"play":"That thou, Aumerle, didst send two of thy men"},"80":{"play":"To execute the noble duke at Calais."},"81":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Some honest Christian trust me with a gage"},"82":{"play":"That Norfolk lies: here do I throw down this,"},"83":{"play":"If he may be repeal'd, to try his honour."},"84":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: These differences shall all rest under gage"},"85":{"play":"Till Norfolk be repeal'd: repeal'd he shall be,"},"86":{"play":"And, though mine enemy, restored again"},"87":{"play":"To all his lands and signories: when he's return'd,"},"88":{"play":"Against Aumerle we will enforce his trial."},"89":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: That honourable day shall ne'er be seen."},"90":{"play":"Many a time hath banish'd Norfolk fought"},"91":{"play":"For Jesu Christ in glorious Christian field,"},"92":{"play":"Streaming the ensign of the Christian cross"},"93":{"play":"Against black pagans, Turks, and Saracens:"},"94":{"play":"And toil'd with works of war, retired himself"},"95":{"play":"To Italy; and there at Venice gave"},"96":{"play":"His body to that pleasant country's earth,"},"97":{"play":"And his pure soul unto his captain Christ,"},"98":{"play":"Under whose colours he had fought so long."},"99":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Why, bishop, is Norfolk dead?"},"100":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: As surely as I live, my lord."},"101":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Sweet peace conduct his sweet soul to the bosom"},"102":{"play":"Of good old Abraham! Lords appellants,"},"103":{"play":"Your differences shall all rest under gage"},"104":{"play":"Till we assign you to your days of trial."},"105":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Great Duke of Lancaster, I come to thee"},"106":{"play":"From plume-pluck'd Richard; who with willing soul"},"107":{"play":"Adopts thee heir, and his high sceptre yields"},"108":{"play":"To the possession of thy royal hand:"},"109":{"play":"Ascend his throne, descending now from him;"},"110":{"play":"And long live Henry, fourth of that name!"},"111":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: In God's name, I'll ascend the regal throne."},"112":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: Marry. God forbid!"},"113":{"play":"Worst in this royal presence may I speak,"},"114":{"play":"Yet best beseeming me to speak the truth."},"115":{"play":"Would God that any in this noble presence"},"116":{"play":"Were enough noble to be upright judge"},"117":{"play":"Of noble Richard! then true noblesse would"},"118":{"play":"Learn him forbearance from so foul a wrong."},"119":{"play":"What subject can give sentence on his king?"},"120":{"play":"And who sits here that is not Richard's subject?"},"121":{"play":"Thieves are not judged but they are by to hear,"},"122":{"play":"Although apparent guilt be seen in them;"},"123":{"play":"And shall the figure of God's majesty,"},"124":{"play":"His captain, steward, deputy-elect,"},"125":{"play":"Anointed, crowned, planted many years,"},"126":{"play":"Be judged by subject and inferior breath,"},"127":{"play":"And he himself not present? O, forfend it, God,"},"128":{"play":"That in a Christian climate souls refined"},"129":{"play":"Should show so heinous, black, obscene a deed!"},"130":{"play":"I speak to subjects, and a subject speaks,"},"131":{"play":"Stirr'd up by God, thus boldly for his king:"},"132":{"play":"My Lord of Hereford here, whom you call king,"},"133":{"play":"Is a foul traitor to proud Hereford's king:"},"134":{"play":"And if you crown him, let me prophesy:"},"135":{"play":"The blood of English shall manure the ground,"},"136":{"play":"And future ages groan for this foul act;"},"137":{"play":"Peace shall go sleep with Turks and infidels,"},"138":{"play":"And in this seat of peace tumultuous wars"},"139":{"play":"Shall kin with kin and kind with kind confound;"},"140":{"play":"Disorder, horror, fear and mutiny"},"141":{"play":"Shall here inhabit, and this land be call'd"},"142":{"play":"The field of Golgotha and dead men's skulls."},"143":{"play":"O, if you raise this house against this house,"},"144":{"play":"It will the woefullest division prove"},"145":{"play":"That ever fell upon this cursed earth."},"146":{"play":"Prevent it, resist it, let it not be so,"},"147":{"play":"Lest child, child's children, cry against you woe!"},"148":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Well have you argued, sir; and, for your pains,"},"149":{"play":"Of capital treason we arrest you here."},"150":{"play":"My Lord of Westminster, be it your charge"},"151":{"play":"To keep him safely till his day of trial."},"152":{"play":"May it please you, lords, to grant the commons' suit."},"153":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Fetch hither Richard, that in common view"},"154":{"play":"He may surrender; so we shall proceed"},"155":{"play":"Without suspicion."},"156":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: I will be his conduct."},"157":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Lords, you that here are under our arrest,"},"158":{"play":"Procure your sureties for your days of answer."},"159":{"play":"Little are we beholding to your love,"},"160":{"play":"And little look'd for at your helping hands."},"161":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Alack, why am I sent for to a king,"},"162":{"play":"Before I have shook off the regal thoughts"},"163":{"play":"Wherewith I reign'd? I hardly yet have learn'd"},"164":{"play":"To insinuate, flatter, bow, and bend my limbs:"},"165":{"play":"Give sorrow leave awhile to tutor me"},"166":{"play":"To this submission. Yet I well remember"},"167":{"play":"The favours of these men: were they not mine?"},"168":{"play":"Did they not sometime cry, 'all hail!' to me?"},"169":{"play":"So Judas did to Christ: but he, in twelve,"},"170":{"play":"Found truth in all but one: I, in twelve thousand, none."},"171":{"play":"God save the king! Will no man say amen?"},"172":{"play":"Am I both priest and clerk? well then, amen."},"173":{"play":"God save the king! although I be not he;"},"174":{"play":"And yet, amen, if heaven do think him me."},"175":{"play":"To do what service am I sent for hither?"},"176":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: To do that office of thine own good will"},"177":{"play":"Which tired majesty did make thee offer,"},"178":{"play":"The resignation of thy state and crown"},"179":{"play":"To Henry Bolingbroke."},"180":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Give me the crown. Here, cousin, seize the crown;"},"181":{"play":"Here cousin:"},"182":{"play":"On this side my hand, and on that side yours."},"183":{"play":"Now is this golden crown like a deep well"},"184":{"play":"That owes two buckets, filling one another,"},"185":{"play":"The emptier ever dancing in the air,"},"186":{"play":"The other down, unseen and full of water:"},"187":{"play":"That bucket down and full of tears am I,"},"188":{"play":"Drinking my griefs, whilst you mount up on high."},"189":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I thought you had been willing to resign."},"190":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: My crown I am; but still my griefs are mine:"},"191":{"play":"You may my glories and my state depose,"},"192":{"play":"But not my griefs; still am I king of those."},"193":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Part of your cares you give me with your crown."},"194":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Your cares set up do not pluck my cares down."},"195":{"play":"My care is loss of care, by old care done;"},"196":{"play":"Your care is gain of care, by new care won:"},"197":{"play":"The cares I give I have, though given away;"},"198":{"play":"They tend the crown, yet still with me they stay."},"199":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Are you contented to resign the crown?"},"200":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Ay, no; no, ay; for I must nothing be;"},"201":{"play":"Therefore no no, for I resign to thee."},"202":{"play":"Now mark me, how I will undo myself;"},"203":{"play":"I give this heavy weight from off my head"},"204":{"play":"And this unwieldy sceptre from my hand,"},"205":{"play":"The pride of kingly sway from out my heart;"},"206":{"play":"With mine own tears I wash away my balm,"},"207":{"play":"With mine own hands I give away my crown,"},"208":{"play":"With mine own tongue deny my sacred state,"},"209":{"play":"With mine own breath release all duty's rites:"},"210":{"play":"All pomp and majesty I do forswear;"},"211":{"play":"My manors, rents, revenues I forego;"},"212":{"play":"My acts, decrees, and statutes I deny:"},"213":{"play":"God pardon all oaths that are broke to me!"},"214":{"play":"God keep all vows unbroke that swear to thee!"},"215":{"play":"Make me, that nothing have, with nothing grieved,"},"216":{"play":"And thou with all pleased, that hast all achieved!"},"217":{"play":"Long mayst thou live in Richard's seat to sit,"},"218":{"play":"And soon lie Richard in an earthly pit!"},"219":{"play":"God save King Harry, unking'd Richard says,"},"220":{"play":"And send him many years of sunshine days!"},"221":{"play":"What more remains?"},"222":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: No more, but that you read"},"223":{"play":"These accusations and these grievous crimes"},"224":{"play":"Committed by your person and your followers"},"225":{"play":"Against the state and profit of this land;"},"226":{"play":"That, by confessing them, the souls of men"},"227":{"play":"May deem that you are worthily deposed."},"228":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Must I do so? and must I ravel out"},"229":{"play":"My weaved-up folly? Gentle Northumberland,"},"230":{"play":"If thy offences were upon record,"},"231":{"play":"Would it not shame thee in so fair a troop"},"232":{"play":"To read a lecture of them? If thou wouldst,"},"233":{"play":"There shouldst thou find one heinous article,"},"234":{"play":"Containing the deposing of a king"},"235":{"play":"And cracking the strong warrant of an oath,"},"236":{"play":"Mark'd with a blot, damn'd in the book of heaven:"},"237":{"play":"Nay, all of you that stand and look upon,"},"238":{"play":"Whilst that my wretchedness doth bait myself,"},"239":{"play":"Though some of you with Pilate wash your hands"},"240":{"play":"Showing an outward pity; yet you Pilates"},"241":{"play":"Have here deliver'd me to my sour cross,"},"242":{"play":"And water cannot wash away your sin."},"243":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My lord, dispatch; read o'er these articles."},"244":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Mine eyes are full of tears, I cannot see:"},"245":{"play":"And yet salt water blinds them not so much"},"246":{"play":"But they can see a sort of traitors here."},"247":{"play":"Nay, if I turn mine eyes upon myself,"},"248":{"play":"I find myself a traitor with the rest;"},"249":{"play":"For I have given here my soul's consent"},"250":{"play":"To undeck the pompous body of a king;"},"251":{"play":"Made glory base and sovereignty a slave,"},"252":{"play":"Proud majesty a subject, state a peasant."},"253":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My lord,--"},"254":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: No lord of thine, thou haught insulting man,"},"255":{"play":"Nor no man's lord; I have no name, no title,"},"256":{"play":"No, not that name was given me at the font,"},"257":{"play":"But 'tis usurp'd: alack the heavy day,"},"258":{"play":"That I have worn so many winters out,"},"259":{"play":"And know not now what name to call myself!"},"260":{"play":"O that I were a mockery king of snow,"},"261":{"play":"Standing before the sun of Bolingbroke,"},"262":{"play":"To melt myself away in water-drops!"},"263":{"play":"Good king, great king, and yet not greatly good,"},"264":{"play":"An if my word be sterling yet in England,"},"265":{"play":"Let it command a mirror hither straight,"},"266":{"play":"That it may show me what a face I have,"},"267":{"play":"Since it is bankrupt of his majesty."},"268":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Go some of you and fetch a looking-glass."},"269":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: Read o'er this paper while the glass doth come."},"270":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Fiend, thou torment'st me ere I come to hell!"},"271":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Urge it no more, my Lord Northumberland."},"272":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: The commons will not then be satisfied."},"273":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: They shall be satisfied: I'll read enough,"},"274":{"play":"When I do see the very book indeed"},"275":{"play":"Where all my sins are writ, and that's myself."},"276":{"play":"Give me the glass, and therein will I read."},"277":{"play":"No deeper wrinkles yet? hath sorrow struck"},"278":{"play":"So many blows upon this face of mine,"},"279":{"play":"And made no deeper wounds? O flattering glass,"},"280":{"play":"Like to my followers in prosperity,"},"281":{"play":"Thou dost beguile me! Was this face the face"},"282":{"play":"That every day under his household roof"},"283":{"play":"Did keep ten thousand men? was this the face"},"284":{"play":"That, like the sun, did make beholders wink?"},"285":{"play":"Was this the face that faced so many follies,"},"286":{"play":"And was at last out-faced by Bolingbroke?"},"287":{"play":"A brittle glory shineth in this face:"},"288":{"play":"As brittle as the glory is the face;"},"289":{"play":"For there it is, crack'd in a hundred shivers."},"290":{"play":"Mark, silent king, the moral of this sport,"},"291":{"play":"How soon my sorrow hath destroy'd my face."},"292":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: The shadow of your sorrow hath destroy'd"},"293":{"play":"The shadow or your face."},"294":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Say that again."},"295":{"play":"The shadow of my sorrow! ha! let's see:"},"296":{"play":"'Tis very true, my grief lies all within;"},"297":{"play":"And these external manners of laments"},"298":{"play":"Are merely shadows to the unseen grief"},"299":{"play":"That swells with silence in the tortured soul;"},"300":{"play":"There lies the substance: and I thank thee, king,"},"301":{"play":"For thy great bounty, that not only givest"},"302":{"play":"Me cause to wail but teachest me the way"},"303":{"play":"How to lament the cause. I'll beg one boon,"},"304":{"play":"And then be gone and trouble you no more."},"305":{"play":"Shall I obtain it?"},"306":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Name it, fair cousin."},"307":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: 'Fair cousin'? I am greater than a king:"},"308":{"play":"For when I was a king, my flatterers"},"309":{"play":"Were then but subjects; being now a subject,"},"310":{"play":"I have a king here to my flatterer."},"311":{"play":"Being so great, I have no need to beg."},"312":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Yet ask."},"313":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: And shall I have?"},"314":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: You shall."},"315":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Then give me leave to go."},"316":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Whither?"},"317":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Whither you will, so I were from your sights."},"318":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Go, some of you convey him to the Tower."},"319":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: O, good! convey? conveyers are you all,"},"320":{"play":"That rise thus nimbly by a true king's fall."},"321":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: On Wednesday next we solemnly set down"},"322":{"play":"Our coronation: lords, prepare yourselves."},"323":{"play":"BISHOP OF CARLISLE: The woe's to come; the children yet unborn."},"324":{"play":"Shall feel this day as sharp to them as thorn."},"325":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: You holy clergymen, is there no plot"},"326":{"play":"To rid the realm of this pernicious blot?"},"327":{"play":"[Exeunt]"}},"ACT 5 SCENE 1":{"1":{"play":"[Enter QUEEN and Ladies]"},"2":{"play":"QUEEN: This way the king will come; this is the way"},"3":{"play":"To Julius Caesar's ill-erected tower,"},"4":{"play":"To whose flint bosom my condemned lord"},"5":{"play":"Is doom'd a prisoner by proud Bolingbroke:"},"6":{"play":"Here let us rest, if this rebellious earth"},"7":{"play":"Have any resting for her true king's queen."},"8":{"play":"But soft, but see, or rather do not see,"},"9":{"play":"My fair rose wither: yet look up, behold,"},"10":{"play":"That you in pity may dissolve to dew,"},"11":{"play":"And wash him fresh again with true-love tears."},"12":{"play":"Ah, thou, the model where old Troy did stand,"},"13":{"play":"Thou map of honour, thou King Richard's tomb,"},"14":{"play":"And not King Richard; thou most beauteous inn,"},"15":{"play":"Why should hard-favour'd grief be lodged in thee,"},"16":{"play":"When triumph is become an alehouse guest?"},"17":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Join not with grief, fair woman, do not so,"},"18":{"play":"To make my end too sudden: learn, good soul,"},"19":{"play":"To think our former state a happy dream;"},"20":{"play":"From which awaked, the truth of what we are"},"21":{"play":"Shows us but this: I am sworn brother, sweet,"},"22":{"play":"To grim Necessity, and he and I"},"23":{"play":"Will keep a league till death. Hie thee to France"},"24":{"play":"And cloister thee in some religious house:"},"25":{"play":"Our holy lives must win a new world's crown,"},"26":{"play":"Which our profane hours here have stricken down."},"27":{"play":"QUEEN: What, is my Richard both in shape and mind"},"28":{"play":"Transform'd and weaken'd? hath Bolingbroke deposed"},"29":{"play":"Thine intellect? hath he been in thy heart?"},"30":{"play":"The lion dying thrusteth forth his paw,"},"31":{"play":"And wounds the earth, if nothing else, with rage"},"32":{"play":"To be o'erpower'd; and wilt thou, pupil-like,"},"33":{"play":"Take thy correction mildly, kiss the rod,"},"34":{"play":"And fawn on rage with base humility,"},"35":{"play":"Which art a lion and a king of beasts?"},"36":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: A king of beasts, indeed; if aught but beasts,"},"37":{"play":"I had been still a happy king of men."},"38":{"play":"Good sometime queen, prepare thee hence for France:"},"39":{"play":"Think I am dead and that even here thou takest,"},"40":{"play":"As from my death-bed, thy last living leave."},"41":{"play":"In winter's tedious nights sit by the fire"},"42":{"play":"With good old folks and let them tell thee tales"},"43":{"play":"Of woeful ages long ago betid;"},"44":{"play":"And ere thou bid good night, to quit their griefs,"},"45":{"play":"Tell thou the lamentable tale of me"},"46":{"play":"And send the hearers weeping to their beds:"},"47":{"play":"For why, the senseless brands will sympathize"},"48":{"play":"The heavy accent of thy moving tongue"},"49":{"play":"And in compassion weep the fire out;"},"50":{"play":"And some will mourn in ashes, some coal-black,"},"51":{"play":"For the deposing of a rightful king."},"52":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My lord, the mind of Bolingbroke is changed:"},"53":{"play":"You must to Pomfret, not unto the Tower."},"54":{"play":"And, madam, there is order ta'en for you;"},"55":{"play":"With all swift speed you must away to France."},"56":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Northumberland, thou ladder wherewithal"},"57":{"play":"The mounting Bolingbroke ascends my throne,"},"58":{"play":"The time shall not be many hours of age"},"59":{"play":"More than it is ere foul sin gathering head"},"60":{"play":"Shalt break into corruption: thou shalt think,"},"61":{"play":"Though he divide the realm and give thee half,"},"62":{"play":"It is too little, helping him to all;"},"63":{"play":"And he shall think that thou, which know'st the way"},"64":{"play":"To plant unrightful kings, wilt know again,"},"65":{"play":"Being ne'er so little urged, another way"},"66":{"play":"To pluck him headlong from the usurped throne."},"67":{"play":"The love of wicked men converts to fear;"},"68":{"play":"That fear to hate, and hate turns one or both"},"69":{"play":"To worthy danger and deserved death."},"70":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: My guilt be on my head, and there an end."},"71":{"play":"Take leave and part; for you must part forthwith."},"72":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Doubly divorced! Bad men, you violate"},"73":{"play":"A twofold marriage, 'twixt my crown and me,"},"74":{"play":"And then betwixt me and my married wife."},"75":{"play":"Let me unkiss the oath 'twixt thee and me;"},"76":{"play":"And yet not so, for with a kiss 'twas made."},"77":{"play":"Part us, Northumberland; I toward the north,"},"78":{"play":"Where shivering cold and sickness pines the clime;"},"79":{"play":"My wife to France: from whence, set forth in pomp,"},"80":{"play":"She came adorned hither like sweet May,"},"81":{"play":"Sent back like Hallowmas or short'st of day."},"82":{"play":"QUEEN: And must we be divided? must we part?"},"83":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Ay, hand from hand, my love, and heart from heart."},"84":{"play":"QUEEN: Banish us both and send the king with me."},"85":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: That were some love but little policy."},"86":{"play":"QUEEN: Then whither he goes, thither let me go."},"87":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: So two, together weeping, make one woe."},"88":{"play":"Weep thou for me in France, I for thee here;"},"89":{"play":"Better far off than near, be ne'er the near."},"90":{"play":"Go, count thy way with sighs; I mine with groans."},"91":{"play":"QUEEN: So longest way shall have the longest moans."},"92":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Twice for one step I'll groan, the way being short,"},"93":{"play":"And piece the way out with a heavy heart."},"94":{"play":"Come, come, in wooing sorrow let's be brief,"},"95":{"play":"Since, wedding it, there is such length in grief;"},"96":{"play":"One kiss shall stop our mouths, and dumbly part;"},"97":{"play":"Thus give I mine, and thus take I thy heart."},"98":{"play":"QUEEN: Give me mine own again; 'twere no good part"},"99":{"play":"To take on me to keep and kill thy heart."},"100":{"play":"So, now I have mine own again, be gone,"},"101":{"play":"That I might strive to kill it with a groan."},"102":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: We make woe wanton with this fond delay:"},"103":{"play":"Once more, adieu; the rest let sorrow say."}},"ACT 5 SCENE 2":{"1":{"play":"[Enter DUKE OF YORK and DUCHESS OF YORK]"},"2":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: My lord, you told me you would tell the rest,"},"3":{"play":"When weeping made you break the story off,"},"4":{"play":"of our two cousins coming into London."},"5":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Where did I leave?"},"6":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: At that sad stop, my lord,"},"7":{"play":"Where rude misgovern'd hands from windows' tops"},"8":{"play":"Threw dust and rubbish on King Richard's head."},"9":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Then, as I said, the duke, great Bolingbroke,"},"10":{"play":"Mounted upon a hot and fiery steed"},"11":{"play":"Which his aspiring rider seem'd to know,"},"12":{"play":"With slow but stately pace kept on his course,"},"13":{"play":"Whilst all tongues cried 'God save thee,"},"14":{"play":"Bolingbroke!'"},"15":{"play":"You would have thought the very windows spake,"},"16":{"play":"So many greedy looks of young and old"},"17":{"play":"Through casements darted their desiring eyes"},"18":{"play":"Upon his visage, and that all the walls"},"19":{"play":"With painted imagery had said at once"},"20":{"play":"'Jesu preserve thee! welcome, Bolingbroke!'"},"21":{"play":"Whilst he, from the one side to the other turning,"},"22":{"play":"Bareheaded, lower than his proud steed's neck,"},"23":{"play":"Bespake them thus: 'I thank you, countrymen:'"},"24":{"play":"And thus still doing, thus he pass'd along."},"25":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Alack, poor Richard! where rode he the whilst?"},"26":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: As in a theatre, the eyes of men,"},"27":{"play":"After a well-graced actor leaves the stage,"},"28":{"play":"Are idly bent on him that enters next,"},"29":{"play":"Thinking his prattle to be tedious;"},"30":{"play":"Even so, or with much more contempt, men's eyes"},"31":{"play":"Did scowl on gentle Richard; no man cried 'God save him!'"},"32":{"play":"No joyful tongue gave him his welcome home:"},"33":{"play":"But dust was thrown upon his sacred head:"},"34":{"play":"Which with such gentle sorrow he shook off,"},"35":{"play":"His face still combating with tears and smiles,"},"36":{"play":"The badges of his grief and patience,"},"37":{"play":"That had not God, for some strong purpose, steel'd"},"38":{"play":"The hearts of men, they must perforce have melted"},"39":{"play":"And barbarism itself have pitied him."},"40":{"play":"But heaven hath a hand in these events,"},"41":{"play":"To whose high will we bound our calm contents."},"42":{"play":"To Bolingbroke are we sworn subjects now,"},"43":{"play":"Whose state and honour I for aye allow."},"44":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Here comes my son Aumerle."},"45":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Aumerle that was;"},"46":{"play":"But that is lost for being Richard's friend,"},"47":{"play":"And, madam, you must call him Rutland now:"},"48":{"play":"I am in parliament pledge for his truth"},"49":{"play":"And lasting fealty to the new-made king."},"50":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Welcome, my son: who are the violets now"},"51":{"play":"That strew the green lap of the new come spring?"},"52":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Madam, I know not, nor I greatly care not:"},"53":{"play":"God knows I had as lief be none as one."},"54":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Well, bear you well in this new spring of time,"},"55":{"play":"Lest you be cropp'd before you come to prime."},"56":{"play":"What news from Oxford? hold those justs and triumphs?"},"57":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: For aught I know, my lord, they do."},"58":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: You will be there, I know."},"59":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: If God prevent not, I purpose so."},"60":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: What seal is that, that hangs without thy bosom?"},"61":{"play":"Yea, look'st thou pale? let me see the writing."},"62":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: My lord, 'tis nothing."},"63":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: No matter, then, who see it;"},"64":{"play":"I will be satisfied; let me see the writing."},"65":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: I do beseech your grace to pardon me:"},"66":{"play":"It is a matter of small consequence,"},"67":{"play":"Which for some reasons I would not have seen."},"68":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Which for some reasons, sir, I mean to see."},"69":{"play":"I fear, I fear,--"},"70":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: What should you fear?"},"71":{"play":"'Tis nothing but some bond, that he is enter'd into"},"72":{"play":"For gay apparel 'gainst the triumph day."},"73":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Bound to himself! what doth he with a bond"},"74":{"play":"That he is bound to? Wife, thou art a fool."},"75":{"play":"Boy, let me see the writing."},"76":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: I do beseech you, pardon me; I may not show it."},"77":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: I will be satisfied; let me see it, I say."},"78":{"play":"Treason! foul treason! Villain! traitor! slave!"},"79":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: What is the matter, my lord?"},"80":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Ho! who is within there?"},"81":{"play":"Saddle my horse."},"82":{"play":"God for his mercy, what treachery is here!"},"83":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Why, what is it, my lord?"},"84":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Give me my boots, I say; saddle my horse."},"85":{"play":"Now, by mine honour, by my life, by my troth,"},"86":{"play":"I will appeach the villain."},"87":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: What is the matter?"},"88":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Peace, foolish woman."},"89":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: I will not peace. What is the matter, Aumerle."},"90":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Good mother, be content; it is no more"},"91":{"play":"Than my poor life must answer."},"92":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Thy life answer!"},"93":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Bring me my boots: I will unto the king."},"94":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Strike him, Aumerle. Poor boy, thou art amazed."},"95":{"play":"Hence, villain! never more come in my sight."},"96":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Give me my boots, I say."},"97":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Why, York, what wilt thou do?"},"98":{"play":"Wilt thou not hide the trespass of thine own?"},"99":{"play":"Have we more sons? or are we like to have?"},"100":{"play":"Is not my teeming date drunk up with time?"},"101":{"play":"And wilt thou pluck my fair son from mine age,"},"102":{"play":"And rob me of a happy mother's name?"},"103":{"play":"Is he not like thee? is he not thine own?"},"104":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Thou fond mad woman,"},"105":{"play":"Wilt thou conceal this dark conspiracy?"},"106":{"play":"A dozen of them here have ta'en the sacrament,"},"107":{"play":"And interchangeably set down their hands,"},"108":{"play":"To kill the king at Oxford."},"109":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: He shall be none;"},"110":{"play":"We'll keep him here: then what is that to him?"},"111":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Away, fond woman! were he twenty times my son,"},"112":{"play":"I would appeach him."},"113":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Hadst thou groan'd for him"},"114":{"play":"As I have done, thou wouldst be more pitiful."},"115":{"play":"But now I know thy mind; thou dost suspect"},"116":{"play":"That I have been disloyal to thy bed,"},"117":{"play":"And that he is a bastard, not thy son:"},"118":{"play":"Sweet York, sweet husband, be not of that mind:"},"119":{"play":"He is as like thee as a man may be,"},"120":{"play":"Not like to me, or any of my kin,"},"121":{"play":"And yet I love him."},"122":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Make way, unruly woman!"},"123":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: After, Aumerle! mount thee upon his horse;"},"124":{"play":"Spur post, and get before him to the king,"},"125":{"play":"And beg thy pardon ere he do accuse thee."},"126":{"play":"I'll not be long behind; though I be old,"},"127":{"play":"I doubt not but to ride as fast as York:"},"128":{"play":"And never will I rise up from the ground"},"129":{"play":"Till Bolingbroke have pardon'd thee. Away, be gone!"}},"ACT 5 SCENE 3":{"1":{"play":"[Enter HENRY BOLINGBROKE, HENRY PERCY, and other Lords]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Can no man tell me of my unthrifty son?"},"3":{"play":"'Tis full three months since I did see him last;"},"4":{"play":"If any plague hang over us, 'tis he."},"5":{"play":"I would to God, my lords, he might be found:"},"6":{"play":"Inquire at London, 'mongst the taverns there,"},"7":{"play":"For there, they say, he daily doth frequent,"},"8":{"play":"With unrestrained loose companions,"},"9":{"play":"Even such, they say, as stand in narrow lanes,"},"10":{"play":"And beat our watch, and rob our passengers;"},"11":{"play":"Which he, young wanton and effeminate boy,"},"12":{"play":"Takes on the point of honour to support"},"13":{"play":"So dissolute a crew."},"14":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: My lord, some two days since I saw the prince,"},"15":{"play":"And told him of those triumphs held at Oxford."},"16":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: And what said the gallant?"},"17":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: His answer was, he would unto the stews,"},"18":{"play":"And from the common'st creature pluck a glove,"},"19":{"play":"And wear it as a favour; and with that"},"20":{"play":"He would unhorse the lustiest challenger."},"21":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: As dissolute as desperate; yet through both"},"22":{"play":"I see some sparks of better hope, which elder years"},"23":{"play":"May happily bring forth. But who comes here?"},"24":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Where is the king?"},"25":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: What means our cousin, that he stares and looks"},"26":{"play":"So wildly?"},"27":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: God save your grace! I do beseech your majesty,"},"28":{"play":"To have some conference with your grace alone."},"29":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Withdraw yourselves, and leave us here alone."},"30":{"play":"What is the matter with our cousin now?"},"31":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: For ever may my knees grow to the earth,"},"32":{"play":"My tongue cleave to my roof within my mouth"},"33":{"play":"Unless a pardon ere I rise or speak."},"34":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Intended or committed was this fault?"},"35":{"play":"If on the first, how heinous e'er it be,"},"36":{"play":"To win thy after-love I pardon thee."},"37":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Then give me leave that I may turn the key,"},"38":{"play":"That no man enter till my tale be done."},"39":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Have thy desire."},"40":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: [Within]  My liege, beware; look to thyself;"},"41":{"play":"Thou hast a traitor in thy presence there."},"42":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Villain, I'll make thee safe."},"43":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Stay thy revengeful hand; thou hast no cause to fear."},"44":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: [Within]  Open the door, secure, foolhardy king:"},"45":{"play":"Shall I for love speak treason to thy face?"},"46":{"play":"Open the door, or I will break it open."},"47":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: What is the matter, uncle? speak;"},"48":{"play":"Recover breath; tell us how near is danger,"},"49":{"play":"That we may arm us to encounter it."},"50":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Peruse this writing here, and thou shalt know"},"51":{"play":"The treason that my haste forbids me show."},"52":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Remember, as thou read'st, thy promise pass'd:"},"53":{"play":"I do repent me; read not my name there"},"54":{"play":"My heart is not confederate with my hand."},"55":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: It was, villain, ere thy hand did set it down."},"56":{"play":"I tore it from the traitor's bosom, king;"},"57":{"play":"Fear, and not love, begets his penitence:"},"58":{"play":"Forget to pity him, lest thy pity prove"},"59":{"play":"A serpent that will sting thee to the heart."},"60":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: O heinous, strong and bold conspiracy!"},"61":{"play":"O loyal father of a treacherous son!"},"62":{"play":"Thou sheer, immaculate and silver fountain,"},"63":{"play":"From when this stream through muddy passages"},"64":{"play":"Hath held his current and defiled himself!"},"65":{"play":"Thy overflow of good converts to bad,"},"66":{"play":"And thy abundant goodness shall excuse"},"67":{"play":"This deadly blot in thy digressing son."},"68":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: So shall my virtue be his vice's bawd;"},"69":{"play":"And he shall spend mine honour with his shame,"},"70":{"play":"As thriftless sons their scraping fathers' gold."},"71":{"play":"Mine honour lives when his dishonour dies,"},"72":{"play":"Or my shamed life in his dishonour lies:"},"73":{"play":"Thou kill'st me in his life; giving him breath,"},"74":{"play":"The traitor lives, the true man's put to death."},"75":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: [Within]  What ho, my liege! for God's sake,"},"76":{"play":"let me in."},"77":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: What shrill-voiced suppliant makes this eager cry?"},"78":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: A woman, and thy aunt, great king; 'tis I."},"79":{"play":"Speak with me, pity me, open the door."},"80":{"play":"A beggar begs that never begg'd before."},"81":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Our scene is alter'd from a serious thing,"},"82":{"play":"And now changed to 'The Beggar and the King.'"},"83":{"play":"My dangerous cousin, let your mother in:"},"84":{"play":"I know she is come to pray for your foul sin."},"85":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: If thou do pardon, whosoever pray,"},"86":{"play":"More sins for this forgiveness prosper may."},"87":{"play":"This fester'd joint cut off, the rest rest sound;"},"88":{"play":"This let alone will all the rest confound."},"89":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: O king, believe not this hard-hearted man!"},"90":{"play":"Love loving not itself none other can."},"91":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Thou frantic woman, what dost thou make here?"},"92":{"play":"Shall thy old dugs once more a traitor rear?"},"93":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Sweet York, be patient. Hear me, gentle liege."},"94":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Rise up, good aunt."},"95":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Not yet, I thee beseech:"},"96":{"play":"For ever will I walk upon my knees,"},"97":{"play":"And never see day that the happy sees,"},"98":{"play":"Till thou give joy; until thou bid me joy,"},"99":{"play":"By pardoning Rutland, my transgressing boy."},"100":{"play":"DUKE OF AUMERLE: Unto my mother's prayers I bend my knee."},"101":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Against them both my true joints bended be."},"102":{"play":"Ill mayst thou thrive, if thou grant any grace!"},"103":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Pleads he in earnest? look upon his face;"},"104":{"play":"His eyes do drop no tears, his prayers are in jest;"},"105":{"play":"His words come from his mouth, ours from our breast:"},"106":{"play":"He prays but faintly and would be denied;"},"107":{"play":"We pray with heart and soul and all beside:"},"108":{"play":"His weary joints would gladly rise, I know;"},"109":{"play":"Our knees shall kneel till to the ground they grow:"},"110":{"play":"His prayers are full of false hypocrisy;"},"111":{"play":"Ours of true zeal and deep integrity."},"112":{"play":"Our prayers do out-pray his; then let them have"},"113":{"play":"That mercy which true prayer ought to have."},"114":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Good aunt, stand up."},"115":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Nay, do not say, 'stand up;'"},"116":{"play":"Say, 'pardon' first, and afterwards 'stand up.'"},"117":{"play":"And if I were thy nurse, thy tongue to teach,"},"118":{"play":"'Pardon' should be the first word of thy speech."},"119":{"play":"I never long'd to hear a word till now;"},"120":{"play":"Say 'pardon,' king; let pity teach thee how:"},"121":{"play":"The word is short, but not so short as sweet;"},"122":{"play":"No word like 'pardon' for kings' mouths so meet."},"123":{"play":"DUKE OF YORK: Speak it in French, king; say, 'pardonne moi.'"},"124":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Dost thou teach pardon pardon to destroy?"},"125":{"play":"Ah, my sour husband, my hard-hearted lord,"},"126":{"play":"That set'st the word itself against the word!"},"127":{"play":"Speak 'pardon' as 'tis current in our land;"},"128":{"play":"The chopping French we do not understand."},"129":{"play":"Thine eye begins to speak; set thy tongue there;"},"130":{"play":"Or in thy piteous heart plant thou thine ear;"},"131":{"play":"That hearing how our plaints and prayers do pierce,"},"132":{"play":"Pity may move thee 'pardon' to rehearse."},"133":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Good aunt, stand up."},"134":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: I do not sue to stand;"},"135":{"play":"Pardon is all the suit I have in hand."},"136":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: I pardon him, as God shall pardon me."},"137":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: O happy vantage of a kneeling knee!"},"138":{"play":"Yet am I sick for fear: speak it again;"},"139":{"play":"Twice saying 'pardon' doth not pardon twain,"},"140":{"play":"But makes one pardon strong."},"141":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: With all my heart"},"142":{"play":"I pardon him."},"143":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: A god on earth thou art."},"144":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: But for our trusty brother-in-law and the abbot,"},"145":{"play":"With all the rest of that consorted crew,"},"146":{"play":"Destruction straight shall dog them at the heels."},"147":{"play":"Good uncle, help to order several powers"},"148":{"play":"To Oxford, or where'er these traitors are:"},"149":{"play":"They shall not live within this world, I swear,"},"150":{"play":"But I will have them, if I once know where."},"151":{"play":"Uncle, farewell: and, cousin too, adieu:"},"152":{"play":"Your mother well hath pray'd, and prove you true."},"153":{"play":"DUCHESS OF YORK: Come, my old son: I pray God make thee new."}},"ACT 5 SCENE 4":{"1":{"play":"[Enter EXTON and Servant]"},"2":{"play":"EXTON: Didst thou not mark the king, what words he spake,"},"3":{"play":"'Have I no friend will rid me of this living fear?'"},"4":{"play":"Was it not so?"},"5":{"play":"'Have I no friend?' quoth he: he spake it twice,"},"6":{"play":"And urged it twice together, did he not?"},"7":{"play":"And speaking it, he wistly look'd on me,"},"8":{"play":"And who should say, 'I would thou wert the man'"},"9":{"play":"That would divorce this terror from my heart;'"},"10":{"play":"Meaning the king at Pomfret. Come, let's go:"},"11":{"play":"I am the king's friend, and will rid his foe."}},"ACT 5 SCENE 5":{"1":{"play":"[Enter KING RICHARD]"},"2":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: I have been studying how I may compare"},"3":{"play":"This prison where I live unto the world:"},"4":{"play":"And for because the world is populous"},"5":{"play":"And here is not a creature but myself,"},"6":{"play":"I cannot do it; yet I'll hammer it out."},"7":{"play":"My brain I'll prove the female to my soul,"},"8":{"play":"My soul the father; and these two beget"},"9":{"play":"A generation of still-breeding thoughts,"},"10":{"play":"And these same thoughts people this little world,"},"11":{"play":"In humours like the people of this world,"},"12":{"play":"For no thought is contented. The better sort,"},"13":{"play":"As thoughts of things divine, are intermix'd"},"14":{"play":"With scruples and do set the word itself"},"15":{"play":"Against the word:"},"16":{"play":"As thus, 'Come, little ones,' and then again,"},"17":{"play":"'It is as hard to come as for a camel"},"18":{"play":"To thread the postern of a small needle's eye.'"},"19":{"play":"Thoughts tending to ambition, they do plot"},"20":{"play":"Unlikely wonders; how these vain weak nails"},"21":{"play":"May tear a passage through the flinty ribs"},"22":{"play":"Of this hard world, my ragged prison walls,"},"23":{"play":"And, for they cannot, die in their own pride."},"24":{"play":"Thoughts tending to content flatter themselves"},"25":{"play":"That they are not the first of fortune's slaves,"},"26":{"play":"Nor shall not be the last; like silly beggars"},"27":{"play":"Who sitting in the stocks refuge their shame,"},"28":{"play":"That many have and others must sit there;"},"29":{"play":"And in this thought they find a kind of ease,"},"30":{"play":"Bearing their own misfortunes on the back"},"31":{"play":"Of such as have before endured the like."},"32":{"play":"Thus play I in one person many people,"},"33":{"play":"And none contented: sometimes am I king;"},"34":{"play":"Then treasons make me wish myself a beggar,"},"35":{"play":"And so I am: then crushing penury"},"36":{"play":"Persuades me I was better when a king;"},"37":{"play":"Then am I king'd again: and by and by"},"38":{"play":"Think that I am unking'd by Bolingbroke,"},"39":{"play":"And straight am nothing: but whate'er I be,"},"40":{"play":"Nor I nor any man that but man is"},"41":{"play":"With nothing shall be pleased, till he be eased"},"42":{"play":"With being nothing. Music do I hear?"},"43":{"play":"Ha, ha! keep time: how sour sweet music is,"},"44":{"play":"When time is broke and no proportion kept!"},"45":{"play":"So is it in the music of men's lives."},"46":{"play":"And here have I the daintiness of ear"},"47":{"play":"To cheque time broke in a disorder'd string;"},"48":{"play":"But for the concord of my state and time"},"49":{"play":"Had not an ear to hear my true time broke."},"50":{"play":"I wasted time, and now doth time waste me;"},"51":{"play":"For now hath time made me his numbering clock:"},"52":{"play":"My thoughts are minutes; and with sighs they jar"},"53":{"play":"Their watches on unto mine eyes, the outward watch,"},"54":{"play":"Whereto my finger, like a dial's point,"},"55":{"play":"Is pointing still, in cleansing them from tears."},"56":{"play":"Now sir, the sound that tells what hour it is"},"57":{"play":"Are clamorous groans, which strike upon my heart,"},"58":{"play":"Which is the bell: so sighs and tears and groans"},"59":{"play":"Show minutes, times, and hours: but my time"},"60":{"play":"Runs posting on in Bolingbroke's proud joy,"},"61":{"play":"While I stand fooling here, his Jack o' the clock."},"62":{"play":"This music mads me; let it sound no more;"},"63":{"play":"For though it have holp madmen to their wits,"},"64":{"play":"In me it seems it will make wise men mad."},"65":{"play":"Yet blessing on his heart that gives it me!"},"66":{"play":"For 'tis a sign of love; and love to Richard"},"67":{"play":"Is a strange brooch in this all-hating world."},"68":{"play":"Thanks, noble peer;"},"69":{"play":"The cheapest of us is ten groats too dear."},"70":{"play":"What art thou? and how comest thou hither,"},"71":{"play":"Where no man never comes but that sad dog"},"72":{"play":"That brings me food to make misfortune live?"},"73":{"play":"Rode he on Barbary? Tell me, gentle friend,"},"74":{"play":"How went he under him?"},"75":{"play":"So proud that Bolingbroke was on his back!"},"76":{"play":"That jade hath eat bread from my royal hand;"},"77":{"play":"This hand hath made him proud with clapping him."},"78":{"play":"Would he not stumble? would he not fall down,"},"79":{"play":"Since pride must have a fall, and break the neck"},"80":{"play":"Of that proud man that did usurp his back?"},"81":{"play":"Forgiveness, horse! why do I rail on thee,"},"82":{"play":"Since thou, created to be awed by man,"},"83":{"play":"Wast born to bear? I was not made a horse;"},"84":{"play":"And yet I bear a burthen like an ass,"},"85":{"play":"Spurr'd, gall'd and tired by jouncing Bolingbroke."},"86":{"play":"If thou love me, 'tis time thou wert away."},"87":{"play":"[Exit]"},"88":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: Taste of it first, as thou art wont to do."},"89":{"play":"The devil take Henry of Lancaster and thee!"},"90":{"play":"Patience is stale, and I am weary of it."},"91":{"play":"[Enter EXTON and Servants, armed]"},"92":{"play":"KING RICHARD II: How now! what means death in this rude assault?"},"93":{"play":"Villain, thy own hand yields thy death's instrument."},"94":{"play":"Go thou, and fill another room in hell."},"95":{"play":"That hand shall burn in never-quenching fire"},"96":{"play":"That staggers thus my person. Exton, thy fierce hand"},"97":{"play":"Hath with the king's blood stain'd the king's own land."},"98":{"play":"Mount, mount, my soul! thy seat is up on high;"},"99":{"play":"Whilst my gross flesh sinks downward, here to die."},"100":{"play":"EXTON: As full of valour as of royal blood:"},"101":{"play":"Both have I spill'd; O would the deed were good!"},"102":{"play":"For now the devil, that told me I did well,"},"103":{"play":"Says that this deed is chronicled in hell."},"104":{"play":"This dead king to the living king I'll bear"},"105":{"play":"Take hence the rest, and give them burial here."}},"ACT 5 SCENE 6":{"1":{"play":"[Flourish. Enter HENRY BOLINGBROKE, DUKE OF YORK, with other Lords, and Attendants]"},"2":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Kind uncle York, the latest news we hear"},"3":{"play":"Is that the rebels have consumed with fire"},"4":{"play":"Our town of Cicester in Gloucestershire;"},"5":{"play":"But whether they be ta'en or slain we hear not."},"6":{"play":"Welcome, my lord\twhat is the news?"},"7":{"play":"NORTHUMBERLAND: First, to thy sacred state wish I all happiness."},"8":{"play":"The next news is, I have to London sent"},"9":{"play":"The heads of Oxford, Salisbury, Blunt, and Kent:"},"10":{"play":"The manner of their taking may appear"},"11":{"play":"At large discoursed in this paper here."},"12":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: We thank thee, gentle Percy, for thy pains;"},"13":{"play":"And to thy worth will add right worthy gains."},"14":{"play":"LORD FITZWATER: My lord, I have from Oxford sent to London"},"15":{"play":"The heads of Brocas and Sir Bennet Seely,"},"16":{"play":"Two of the dangerous consorted traitors"},"17":{"play":"That sought at Oxford thy dire overthrow."},"18":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Thy pains, Fitzwater, shall not be forgot;"},"19":{"play":"Right noble is thy merit, well I wot."},"20":{"play":"HENRY PERCY: The grand conspirator, Abbot of Westminster,"},"21":{"play":"With clog of conscience and sour melancholy"},"22":{"play":"Hath yielded up his body to the grave;"},"23":{"play":"But here is Carlisle living, to abide"},"24":{"play":"Thy kingly doom and sentence of his pride."},"25":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Carlisle, this is your doom:"},"26":{"play":"Choose out some secret place, some reverend room,"},"27":{"play":"More than thou hast, and with it joy thy life;"},"28":{"play":"So as thou livest in peace, die free from strife:"},"29":{"play":"For though mine enemy thou hast ever been,"},"30":{"play":"High sparks of honour in thee have I seen."},"31":{"play":"EXTON: Great king, within this coffin I present"},"32":{"play":"Thy buried fear: herein all breathless lies"},"33":{"play":"The mightiest of thy greatest enemies,"},"34":{"play":"Richard of Bordeaux, by me hither brought."},"35":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: Exton, I thank thee not; for thou hast wrought"},"36":{"play":"A deed of slander with thy fatal hand"},"37":{"play":"Upon my head and all this famous land."},"38":{"play":"EXTON: From your own mouth, my lord, did I this deed."},"39":{"play":"HENRY BOLINGBROKE: They love not poison that do poison need,"},"40":{"play":"Nor do I thee: though I did wish him dead,"},"41":{"play":"I hate the murderer, love him murdered."},"42":{"play":"The guilt of conscience take thou for thy labour,"},"43":{"play":"But neither my good word nor princely favour:"},"44":{"play":"With Cain go wander through shades of night,"},"45":{"play":"And never show thy head by day nor light."},"46":{"play":"Lords, I protest, my soul is full of woe,"},"47":{"play":"That blood should sprinkle me to make me grow:"},"48":{"play":"Come, mourn with me for that I do lament,"},"49":{"play":"And put on sullen black incontinent:"},"50":{"play":"I'll make a voyage to the Holy Land,"},"51":{"play":"To wash this blood off from my guilty hand:"},"52":{"play":"March sadly after; grace my mournings here;"},"53":{"play":"In weeping after this untimely bier."}}}